{"title_page": "Horologium (constellation)", "text_new": "{{Infobox constellation|\nname = Horologium |\nabbreviation = Hor |\ngenitive = Horologii |\npronounce = {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u0252r|\u0259|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|d\u0292|i|\u0259m|,_|-|\u02c8|l|\u0252|-}},{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2016-01-21|Horologium}}}}<br />genitive {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u0252r|\u0259|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|d\u0292|i|\u02cc|a\u026a|,_|-|\u02c8|l|\u0252|-}} |\nsymbolism = The [[pendulum clock|Pendulum Clock]] |\nRA = {{RA|3}} |\ndec= {{DEC|\u221260}} |\nfamily = [[La Caille Family|La Caille]] |\nquadrant = SQ1 |\nareatotal = 249 |\narearank = 58th |\nnumbermainstars = 6 |\nnumberbfstars = 10 |\nnumberstarsplanets = 4 |\nnumberbrightstars = 0 |\nnumbernearbystars = 1 |\nbrighteststarname = [[Alpha Horologii|\u03b1 Hor]] |\nstarmagnitude = 3.85 |\nneareststarname = [[GJ 1061]] |\nstardistancely = 11.99 |\nstardistancepc = 3.66 |\nnumbermessierobjects = 0 |\nmeteorshowers = 0 |\nbordering = [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]]<br />[[Hydrus]]<br />[[Reticulum]]<br />[[Dorado (constellation)|Dorado]]<br />[[Caelum]] |\nlatmax = [[30th parallel north|30]] |\nlatmin = [[South Pole|90]] |\nmonth = December |\nnotes=}}\n'''Horologium''' (Latin {{lang|la|h\u014drologium}}, from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|\u1f61\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd}}, {{lit|an instrument for telling the hour}}) is a [[constellation]] of six faintly visible stars in the [[southern celestial hemisphere]]. It was first described by the French astronomer [[Nicolas-Louis de Lacaille]] in 1756 and visualized by him as a clock with a pendulum and a second hand. In 1922 the constellation was redefined by the [[International Astronomical Union]] (IAU) as a region of the celestial sphere containing Lacaille's stars, and has since been an [[IAU designated constellations|IAU designated constellation]]. Horologium's associated region is wholly visible to observers south of [[23rd parallel north|23\u00b0N]].\n\nThe constellation's brightest [[star]]\u2014and the only one brighter than an [[apparent magnitude]] of 4\u2014is [[Alpha Horologii]] (at 3.85), an ageing orange [[giant star]] that has swollen to around 11 times the diameter of the Sun. The [[Mira variable|long-period variable-brightness]] star, [[R Horologii]] (4.7 to 14.3), has one of the largest variations in brightness known for stars in the night sky visible to the unaided eye. Four star systems in the constellation are known to have [[exoplanet]]s; one\u2014[[Gliese 1061]]\u2014contains an exoplanet in its [[circumstellar habitable zone|habitable zone]].\n\n==History==\nThe French astronomer [[Nicolas Louis de Lacaille]] first described the [[constellation]] <!-- in French (obviously)--> as ''l'Horloge \u00e0 pendule & \u00e0 secondes'' (Clock with pendulum and seconds hand) in 1756,<ref name=ridpathlac>{{cite web |url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/lacaille.htm |title=Lacaille's Southern Planisphere of 1756 |work=Star Tales |author=Ridpath, Ian |publisher=Self-published |accessdate=19 March 2016 |author-link=Ian Ridpath |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193222/http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/lacaille.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Lacaille, Nicolas Louis |year=1756 |title=Relation abr\u00e9g\u00e9e du Voyage fait par ordre du Roi au cap de Bonne-esp\u00e9rance |journal=M\u00e9moires de l'Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Sciences |pages=519\u2013592 [588] |url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k35505/f786 |language=French |access-date=2016-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119115952/http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k35505/f786 |archive-date=2016-11-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> after he had observed and catalogued almost 10,000 southern stars during a two-year stay at the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. He devised fourteen new constellations in previously uncharted regions of the [[southern celestial hemisphere]], which were not visible from Europe. All but one honoured [[scientific instrument]]s, and so symbolised the [[Age of Enlightenment]].{{efn|1=The exception is [[Mensa (constellation)|Mensa]], named for [[Table Mountain]]. The other twelve (alongside Horologium) are [[Antlia]], [[Caelum]], [[Circinus]], [[Fornax]], [[Microscopium]], [[Norma (constellation)|Norma]], [[Octans]], [[Pictor]], [[Pyxis]], [[Reticulum]], [[Sculptor (constellation)|Sculptor]] and [[Telescopium]].<ref name=wagman/>}} The constellation name was [[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] to ''Horologium'' in a catalogue and updated chart published posthumously in 1763.<ref name=wagman>{{cite book |last=Wagman |first=Morton |date=2003 |title=Lost Stars: Lost, Missing and Troublesome Stars from the Catalogues of Johannes Bayer, Nicholas Louis de Lacaille, John Flamsteed, and Sundry Others |publisher=The McDonald & Woodward Publishing Company |location=Blacksburg, Virginia |isbn=978-0939923786 |pages=6\u20137, 169\u2013170}}</ref><!-- Cites previous three sentences --> The Latin term is ultimately derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] \u1f61\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd, for an instrument for telling the hour.<ref>{{cite web|title=horologe, noun|url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/88531#eid1280061|publisher=Oxford English Dictionary|accessdate=26 December 2019}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Horologium declension coordinates and visibility.jpg|left|thumb|Horologium constellation: showing the tangent line, or viewer's horizon, at latitude approx 23 N, which is parallel to the line of -67.04 declension, the lower declination boundary of the constellation.]]\nCovering a total of 248.9 [[square degree]]s or 0.603% of the sky, Horologium ranks 58th in area out of the 88 modern constellations.<ref name=tirionconst>{{cite web | url=http://www.ianridpath.com/constellations1.htm | title=Constellations: Andromeda\u2013Indus | work=Star Tales | author=Ridpath, Ian | publisher=self-published | accessdate=19 March 2016 | author-link=Ian Ridpath | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BScsVZIp?url=http://www.ianridpath.com/constellations1.htm | archive-date=16 October 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Its position in the southern celestial hemisphere means the whole constellation is visible to observers south of [[23rd parallel north|23\u00b0N]].<ref name=tirionconst/>{{efn|1=While parts of the constellation technically rise above the horizon to observers between the latitudes of 23\u00b0N and [[50th parallel north|50\u00b0N]], those stars within a few degrees of the horizon are difficult to see.<ref name=tirionconst/>}} Horologium is bordered by five constellations: [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]] (the [[Po (river)|Po]] river), [[Caelum]] (the [[chisel]]), [[Reticulum]] (the [[reticle]]), [[Dorado]] (the [[dolphin]]/[[swordfish]]), and [[Hydrus]] (the ''male'' [[water snake (disambiguation)|water snake]]). The three-letter abbreviation for the constellation, as adopted by the [[International Astronomical Union]] in 1922, is \"Hor\".<ref name=\"pa30_469\">{{cite journal | last=Russell | first=Henry Norris |author-link=Henry Norris Russell | title=The New International Symbols for the Constellations | journal=[[Popular Astronomy (US magazine)|Popular Astronomy]] | volume=30 | page=469 | bibcode=1922PA.....30..469R | date=1922}}</ref> The official constellation boundaries are defined by a twenty-two-sided polygon (''illustrated in infobox''). In the [[equatorial coordinate system]], the [[right ascension]] coordinates of these borders lie between {{RA|02|12.8}} and {{RA|04|20.3}}, while the [[declination]] coordinates are between \u221239.64\u00b0 and \u221267.04\u00b0.<ref name=\"boundary\">{{Cite journal | title=Horologium, Constellation Boundary | journal=The Constellations | publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]] | url=http://www.iau.org/public/constellations/#hor | accessdate=19 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605024208/http://www.iau.org/public/constellations/#hor | archive-date=5 June 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n==Features==\n[[Image:Constellation Horologium.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The constellation Horologium as it can be seen by the [[naked eye]]|alt=several scattered stars seen in evening sky]]\n\n===Stars===\n{{see also|List of stars in Horologium}}\n\nHorologium has one star brighter than [[apparent magnitude]] 4,<ref name=\"cambridge\">{{cite book|author1=Moore, Patrick |author2=Tirion, Wil |title=Cambridge Guide to Stars and Planets|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge, UK|date=1997|page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00moor/page/190 190]|isbn=978-0521585828|url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00moor|url-access=registration }}</ref> and 41 stars brighter than or equal to magnitude 6.5.{{efn|1=Objects of magnitude 6.5 are among the faintest visible to the unaided eye from locations between suburban and rural areas in [[night sky|night skies]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyandtelescope.com/resources/darksky/3304011.html?page=1&c=y |title=The Bortle Dark-Sky Scale |last=Bortle |first=John E. |date=February 2001 |work=[[Sky & Telescope]] |publisher=Sky Publishing Corporation |accessdate=1 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925104130/http://www.skyandtelescope.com/resources/darksky/3304011.html?page=1&c=y |archive-date=25 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}<ref name=\"tirionconst\"/> Lacaille charted and designated 11 stars in the constellation, giving them the [[Bayer designation]]s [[Alpha Horologii|Alpha]] (\u03b1 Hor) through [[Lambda Horologii]] (\u03bb Hor) in 1756. In the mid-19th century, English astronomer [[Francis Baily]] removed the designations of two\u2014[[HR 762|Epsilon]] and [[HR 821|Theta Horologii]]\u2014as he held they were too faint to warrant naming. He was unable to find a star that corresponded to the coordinates of Lacaille's [[Beta Horologii]]. Determining that the coordinates were wrong, he assigned the designation to another star. Kappa Horologii, too, was unable to be verified\u2014although it most likely was the star [[HD 18292]]\u2014and the name fell out of use. In 1879, American astronomer [[Benjamin Apthorp Gould]] assigned designations to what became [[Mu Horologii|Mu]] and [[Nu Horologii]] as he felt they were bright enough to warrant them.<ref name=wagman/>\n\nAt magnitude 3.9, Alpha Horologii is the brightest star in the constellation, located 115 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.5) [[light-year]]s from Earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\">{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen | title=Validation of the New Hipparcos Reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | date=2007 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 | arxiv=0708.1752}}</ref> German astronomer [[Johann Elert Bode]] depicted it as the pendulum of the clock, while Lacaille made it one of the weights.<ref name=ridphor>{{cite web | url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/horologium.htm | title=Horologium | work=Star Tales | author=Ridpath, Ian | author-link=Ian Ridpath | publisher=self-published | accessdate=21 January 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822192026/http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/horologium.htm | archive-date=22 August 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> It is an orange [[giant star]] of [[Stellar classification#Spectral types|spectral type]] K2III that has swollen to around 11 times the diameter of the Sun, having spent much of its life as a [[A-type main-sequence star|white main-sequence star]].<ref name=kaleralfa>{{cite web |last1=Kaler |first1=Jim |title=Alpha Horologii |url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/alphahor.html |website=James Kaler's Stars |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408175028/http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/alphahor.html |archive-date=8 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At an estimated 1.55 times the [[mass of the Sun]],<ref name=\"Liu 2007\">{{cite journal|author=Liu, Y. J.|author2=Zhao, G.|author3=Shi, J. R.|author4=Pietrzy\u0144ski, G.|author5=Gieren, W.|date=2007|title=The Abundances of Nearby Red Clump Giants|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=382|issue=2|pages=553\u2013566|bibcode=2007MNRAS.382..553L|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2007.11852.x|doi-access=free}}</ref> it is radiating 38 times the [[Sun's luminosity]] from its [[photosphere]] at an [[effective temperature|effective (surface) temperature]] of 5,028{{nbsp}}[[Kelvin|K]].<ref name=Mcdonald>{{cite journal|author=McDonald, I.|author2=Zijlstra, A. A.|author3=Boyer, M. L.|date=2012|title=Fundamental Parameters and Infrared Excesses of Hipparcos Stars|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=427|issue=1|pages=343\u2013357|bibcode=2012MNRAS.427..343M|arxiv = 1208.2037 |doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2966.2012.21873.x }}</ref>\n\nAt magnitude 4.93, [[Delta Horologii]] is the second-brightest star in the constellation,<ref name=kalerbeta>{{cite web |last1=Kaler |first1=Jim |title=Beta Horologii |url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/betahor.html |website=James Kaler's Stars |date=21 January 2011 |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417224118/http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/betahor.html |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and forms a wide [[Double star|optical double]] with Alpha.<ref name=arnold>{{cite book |author=Arnold, H.J.P |author2=Doherty, Paul |author3=Moore, Patrick |title=The Photographic Atlas of the Stars |publisher=CRC Press |location=Boca Raton, Florida |date=1999 |page=48 |isbn=978-0750306546 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YjcvJUfnWBAC&pg=PA48}}</ref> Delta itself is a true [[Binary star|binary]] system composed of a white main sequence star of spectral type A5V that is 1.41 times as massive as the Sun with a magnitude of 5.15 and its fainter companion of magnitude 7.29.<ref name=Eggleton2008>{{cite journal | last1=Eggleton | first1=P. P. | last2=Tokovinin | first2=A. A. | title=A Catalogue of Multiplicity among Bright Stellar Systems | journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] | volume=389 | issue=2 | pages=869\u2013879 | date=2008 | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2008.13596.x | bibcode=2008MNRAS.389..869E |arxiv = 0806.2878 }}</ref> The system is located 179 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}4) light-years from the earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n\nAt magnitude 5.0, Beta Horologii is a [[white giant]] 63 times as luminous as the Sun with an effective temperature of 8,303{{nbsp}}K.<ref name=Mcdonald/> It is 312 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}4) light-years from Earth,<ref name=GaiaDR2beta>{{cite DR2|4720282071779657600}}</ref> and has been little-studied.<ref name=kalerbeta/> Lambda Horologii is an ageing yellow-white giant star of spectral type F2III that spins around at 140{{nbsp}}km/second, and is hence mildly flattened at its poles ([[Spheroid#Oblate spheroids|oblate]]).<ref name=belle>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/s00159-012-0051-2| title = Interferometric Observations of Rapidly Rotating Stars| year = 2012| last1 = Belle | first1 = G. T. | journal = The Astronomy and Astrophysics Review| volume = 20| issue = 1| page = 51| bibcode = 2012A&ARv..20...51V|arxiv = 1204.2572 }}</ref> It is 161 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}1) light-years from Earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n\nWith a magnitude of 5.24,<ref name=apj800_1_5/> Nu Horologii is a white main sequence star of spectral type A2V located 169 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}1) light-years from Earth<ref name=GaiaDR2nu>{{cite DR2|4721400206385912960}}</ref> that is around 1.9 times as massive as the Sun. Estimated to be around 540&nbsp;million years old, it has a [[debris disk]] that appears to have two components: an inner disk is orbiting at a distance of {{val|96|+9|\u221237|u=[[Astronomical unit|AU]]}}, while an outer disk lies {{val|410|+24|\u221296|u= AU}} from the star. The estimated mass of the disks is {{val|0.13|\u00b10.07|u=%}} the mass of the Earth.<ref name=apj800_1_5>{{cite journal| last1=Meshkat | first1=Tiffany | last2=Bailey | first2=Vanessa P. | last3=Su | first3=Kate Y. L. | last4=Kenworthy | first4=Matthew A. | last5=Mamajek | first5=Eric E. | last6=Hinz | first6=Philip M. | last7=Smith | first7=Paul S. | title=Searching for Planets in Holey Debris Disks with the Apodizing Phase Plate | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=800 | issue=1 | id=5 | date=2015 | doi=10.1088/0004-637X/800/1/5 | bibcode=2015ApJ...800....5M | arxiv=1412.5179 | page=5}}</ref>\n\nHorologium has several [[variable star]]s. [[R Horologii]] is a [[red giant]] [[Mira variable]] with one of the widest ranges in brightness known of stars in the night sky visible to the unaided eye.<ref name=privett>{{cite book|last=Privett|first=Grant|author2=Jones, Kevin|title=The Constellation Observing Atlas|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|location=New York|date=2013|page=102|isbn=978-1461476481|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uN69BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|access-date=2016-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328183439/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uN69BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|archive-date=2016-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref> It is around 1,000 light-years from Earth.<ref name=GaiaDR2r>{{cite DR2|4748477123328077696}}</ref> It has a minimum magnitude of 14.3 and a maximum magnitude of 4.7, with a period of approximately 13 months.<ref name=ridpath2017/> T and U Horologii are also Mira variables.<ref name=arnold/> The [[Astronomical Society of Southern Africa]] reported in 2003 that observations of these two stars were needed as data on their light curves was incomplete.<ref name=cooper>{{cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Tim|date=2003|title=Presidential Address: Amateur Observations \u2013 Successes and Opportunities|journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa|volume=62|pages=234\u2013240|bibcode=2003MNSSA..62..234C}}</ref> [[TW Horologii]] is a [[Semiregular variable star|semiregular variable]] red giant star that is classified as a [[carbon star]],<ref name=ridpath2017/> and is 1,370 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}70) light-years from Earth.<ref name=GaiaDR2tw>{{cite DR2|4727337637895749888}}</ref>\n\n[[Iota Horologii]] is a yellow-white dwarf star 1.23 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.12) times as massive and 1.16 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.04) times as wide as the Sun with a [[Stellar classification#Spectra types|spectral type]] of F8V,<ref name=\"Bruntt2010\">{{cite journal | title=Accurate Fundamental Parameters for 23 Bright Solar-type Stars | last1=Bruntt | first1=H. | last2=Bedding | first2=T. R. | last3=Quirion | first3=P.-O. | last4=Lo Curto | first4=G. | last5=Carrier | first5=F. | last6=Smalley | first6=B. | last7=Dall | first7=T. H. | last8=Arentoft | first8=T. | last9=Bazot | first9=M. | journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society | volume=405 | issue=3 | pages=1907\u20131923 | year=2010 | arxiv=1002.4268 | bibcode=2010MNRAS.405.1907B | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2010.16575.x }}</ref> 57 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.05) light-years from Earth.<ref name=\"Gaia DR2iota\">{{Cite Gaia DR2|4745373133284418816}}</ref> Its chemical profile, movement and age indicate it formed within the [[Hyades cluster]] but has drifted around 130 light-years away from the other members.<ref name=\"Vauclair2008\">{{cite journal | title=The Exoplanet-host Star Iota Horologii: an Evaporated Member of the Primordial Hyades Cluster | last1=Vauclair | first1=S. | last2=Laymand | first2=M. | last3=Bouchy | first3=F. | last4=Vauclair | first4=G. | last5=Hui Bon Hoa | first5=A. | last6=Charpinet | first6=S. | last7=Bazot | first7=M. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=482 | issue=2 | pages=L5\u2013L8 | year=2008 | arxiv=0803.2029v1 | bibcode=2008A&A...482L...5V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20079342 }}</ref> It has a planet at least 2.5 times as massive as Jupiter orbiting it every 307 days.<ref name=\"Zechmeister2013\">{{cite journal | title=The Planet Search Programme at the ESO CES and HARPS. IV. The Search for Jupiter Analogues around Solar-like Stars | last1=Zechmeister | first1=M. | last2=K\u00fcrster | first2=M. | last3=Endl | first3=M. | last4=Lo Curto | first4=G. | last5=Hartman | first5=H. | last6=Nilsson | first6=H. | last7=Henning | first7=T. | last8=Hatzes | first8=A. P. | last9=Cochran | first9=W. D. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=552 | at=A78 | year=2013 | bibcode=2013A&A...552A..78Z | arxiv=1211.7263 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201116551 }}</ref> [[HD 27631]] is a Sun-like star located 164 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.3) light-years from Earth<ref name=GaiaDR2HD27631>{{cite DR2|4840050395924931968}}</ref> which was found to have a planet at least 1.45 times as massive as Jupiter that takes 2,208 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}66) days (six years) to complete an orbit.<ref name=\"Marmier2013\">{{cite journal | title=The CORALIE Survey for Southern Extrasolar Planets XVII. New and Updated Long Period and Massive Planets | last1=Marmier | first1=M. | last2=S\u00e9gransan | first2=D. | last3=Udry | first3=S. | last4=Mayor | first4=M. | last5=Pepe | first5=F. | last6=Queloz | first6=D. | last7=Lovis | first7=C. | last8=Naef | first8=D. | last9=Santos | first9=N. C. | last10=Alonso | first10=R. | last11=Alves | first11=S. | last12=Berthet | first12=S. | last13=Chazelas | first13=B. | last14=Demory | first14=B.-O. | last15=Dumusque | first15=X. | last16=Eggenberger | first16=A. | last17=Figueira | first17=P. | last18=Gillon | first18=M. | last19=Hagelberg | first19=J. | last20=Lendl | first20=M. | last21=Mardling | first21=R. A. | last22=M\u00e9gevand | first22=D. | last23=Neveu | first23=M. | last24=Sahlmann | first24=J. | last25=Sosnowska | first25=D. | last26=Tewes | first26=M. | last27=Triaud | first27=A. H. M. J. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=551 | at=A90 | date=2013 | arxiv=1211.6444 | bibcode=2013A&A...551A..90M | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201219639 }}</ref> [[WASP-120]] is a yellow-white main-sequence star around 1.4 times as massive as the Sun with a spectral type of F5V that is estimated to be 2.6 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.5) billion years old. It has a massive planet around 4.85 times the mass of Jupiter that completes its orbit every 3.6 days, and has an estimated surface temperature of 1,880 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}70){{nbsp}}K.<ref name=\"turner\">{{Cite journal|bibcode=2016PASP..128f4401T|title=WASP-120 b, WASP-122 b, and WASP-123 b: Three Newly Discovered Planets from the WASP-South Survey|journal=Publications of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific|volume=128|issue=964|pages=064401|last1=Turner|first1=O. D|last2=Anderson|first2=D. R|last3=Collier Cameron|first3=A|last4=Delrez|first4=L|last5=Evans|first5=D. F|last6=Gillon|first6=M|last7=Hellier|first7=C|last8=Jehin|first8=E|last9=Lendl|first9=M|last10=Maxted|first10=P. F. L|last11=Pepe|first11=F|last12=Pollacco|first12=D|last13=Queloz|first13=D|last14=S\u00e9gransan|first14=D|last15=Smalley|first15=B|last16=Smith|first16=A. M. S|last17=Triaud|first17=A. H. M. J|last18=Udry|first18=S|last19=West|first19=R. G|year=2016|doi=10.1088/1538-3873/128/964/064401|arxiv=1509.02210}}</ref>\n\nWith an apparent magnitude of 13.06, [[Gliese 1061]] is a [[red dwarf]] of spectral type M5.5V that has 12% of the mass and 15% of the diameter of the Sun, and shines with only 0.17% of its [[luminosity]]. Located 12 light-years away from Earth, it is the 20th-closest single star or stellar system to the Sun. In August 2019, it was announced that it had three planets, one of which lay in its [[circumstellar habitable zone|habitable zone]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anglada-Escud\u00e9 |first=G.|last2=Reiners|first2=A.|last3=Pall\u00e9|first3=E.|last4=Ribas|first4=I.|last5=Berdi\u00f1as|first5=Z. M.|last6=L\u00f3pez|first6=C. Rodr\u00edguez|last7=Morales|first7=N.|last8=L\u00f3pez-Gonz\u00e1lez|first8=M. J.|last9=Hambsch|first9=F.-J.|date=2019-08-13|title=Red Dots: A Temperate 1.5 Earth-mass Planet in a Compact Multi-terrestrial Planet System around GJ1061|doi=10.1093/mnras/staa248|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|arxiv=1908.04717v1|volume=493|issue=1|pages=536\u2013550}}</ref>\n\n===Deep-sky objects===\n[[File:NGC 1512 and NGC 1510.jpg|thumb|right|Composite image of NGC 1512 (left) and the dwarf galaxy NGC 1510|alt=A larger spiral galaxy on left and smaller rounder galaxy on right in star field.]]\n\nHorologium is home to many deep-sky objects, including several [[globular cluster]]s. [[NGC 1261]] is a globular cluster of magnitude 8, located 53,000 light-years from Earth.<ref name=ridpath2017>{{cite book | first=Ian |last=Ridpath |first2= Wil | last2= Tirion | year=2017| title=Stars and Planets Guide | publisher= Collins | location= London | isbn=978-0-00-823927-5| page=158}}</ref> It lies 4.7 degrees north-northeast of Mu Horologii.<ref name=bakich/> The globular cluster [[Arp-Madore 1]] is the most remote known globular cluster in the [[Milky Way]] at a distance of {{convert|123.3|kpc|ly|abbr=off}} from Earth.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1093/mnras/stz171|title = Proper Motions and Dynamics of the Milky Way Globular Cluster System from Gaia DR2|journal = Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume = 484|issue = 2|pages = 2832\u20132850|year = 2019|last1 = Vasiliev|first1 = Eugene|bibcode = 2019MNRAS.484.2832V|arxiv = 1807.09775}}</ref>\n\n[[NGC 1512]] is a [[barred spiral galaxy]] 2.1 degrees west-southwest of Alpha Horologii with an apparent magnitude of 10.2.<ref name=bakich>{{cite book |title=1001 Celestial Wonders to See Before You Die: The Best Sky Objects for Star Gazers |first=Michael E. |last=Bakich |publisher=Springer |year=2010 |isbn=978-1441917775 |pages=402, 416}}</ref> About five [[arcmin]] (13.8 [[Parsec#Parsecs and kiloparsecs|kpc]]) away is the [[dwarf galaxy|dwarf]] [[lenticular galaxy]] [[NGC 1510]]. The two are in the process of a merger which has been going on for 400&nbsp;million years.<ref name=Monthly400>{{cite journal |last1=Koribalski |first1=B\u00e4rbel S. |last2=L\u00f3pez-S\u00e1nchez |first2= \u00c1ngel R. |date=2009 |title=Gas Dynamics and Star Formation in the Galaxy Pair NGC 1512/1510 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |volume=400 |issue=4 |page=21 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2009.15610.x |arxiv=0908.4128|bibcode=2009MNRAS.400.1749K}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster]] is a galaxy [[supercluster]], second in size only to the [[Shapley Supercluster]] in the local universe (anything within 200 [[Parsec#Megaparsecs and gigaparsecs|mpc]] of Earth). It contains over 20 [[Abell catalogue|Abell galaxy clusters]] and covers more than 100 deg<sup>2</sup><!-- Is this the same \"degree square\" we see above? If so, it should be linked and \"degree square\" should have the abbreviation posted next to it in (parens). --> of the sky, centered roughly at equatorial coordinates \u03b1 = {{RA|03|19}}, \u03b4 = {{DEC|50|2}}.<ref name=apj130_3>{{cite journal |author1=Fleenor, Matthew C. |author2=Rose, James A. |author3=Christiansen, Wayne A. |author4=Hunstead, Richard W. |authorlink4=Richard Hunstead |author5=Johnston-Hollitt, Melanie |author6=Drinkwater, Michael J. |author7=Saunders, William | title=Large-Scale Velocity Structures in the Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=130 | issue=3 | pages=957\u2013967 |date=September 2005 | doi=10.1086/431972 | bibcode=2005AJ....130..957F |arxiv = astro-ph/0505361 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 2 sentences -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Horologium}}\n* [http://www.allthesky.com/constellations/reticulum/constell.html The Deep Photographic Guide to the Constellations: Horologium]\n* [http://astrojan.eu5.org/reticul.htm The clickable Horologium]\n* [http://www.starrynightphotos.com/constellations/fornax_phoenix.htm Starry Night Photography \u2013 Horologium Constellation]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Stars of Horologium}}\n{{navconstel}}\n{{ConstellationsByLacaille}}\n{{Christiaan Huygens}}\n\n{{Sky|03|00|00|-|60|00|00|10}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Horologium (constellation)| ]]\n[[Category:Southern constellations]]\n[[Category:Constellations listed by Lacaille]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- {{inuse}} -->\n{{Infobox constellation|\nname = Horologium |\nabbreviation = Hor |\ngenitive = Horologii |\npronounce = {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u0252r|\u0259|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|d\u0292|i|\u0259m|,_|-|\u02c8|l|\u0252|-}},{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2016-01-21|Horologium}}}}<br />genitive {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u0252r|\u0259|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|d\u0292|i|\u02cc|a\u026a|,_|-|\u02c8|l|\u0252|-}} |\nsymbolism = The [[pendulum clock|Pendulum Clock]] |\nRA = {{RA|3}} |\ndec= {{DEC|\u221260}} |\nfamily = [[La Caille Family|La Caille]] |\nquadrant = SQ1 |\nareatotal = 249 |\narearank = 58th |\nnumbermainstars = 6 |\nnumberbfstars = 10 |\nnumberstarsplanets = 4 |\nnumberbrightstars = 0 |\nnumbernearbystars = 1 |\nbrighteststarname = [[Alpha Horologii|\u03b1 Hor]] |\nstarmagnitude = 3.85 |\nneareststarname = [[GJ 1061]] |\nstardistancely = 11.99 |\nstardistancepc = 3.66 |\nnumbermessierobjects = 0 |\nmeteorshowers = 0 |\nbordering = [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]]<br />[[Hydrus]]<br />[[Reticulum]]<br />[[Dorado (constellation)|Dorado]]<br />[[Caelum]] |\nlatmax = [[30th parallel north|30]] |\nlatmin = [[South Pole|90]] |\nmonth = December |\nnotes=}}\n'''Horologium''' (Latin {{lang|la|h\u014drologium}}, from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|\u1f61\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd}}, {{lit|an instrument for telling the hour}}) is a [[constellation]] of six faintly visible stars in the [[southern celestial hemisphere]]. It was first described by the French astronomer [[Nicolas-Louis de Lacaille]] in 1756 and visualized by him as a clock with a pendulum and a second hand. In 1922 the constellation was redefined by the [[International Astronomical Union]] (IAU) as a region of the celestial sphere containing Lacaille's stars, and has since been an [[IAU designated constellations|IAU designated constellation]]. Horologium's associated region is wholly visible to observers south of [[23rd parallel north|23\u00b0N]].\n\nThe constellation's brightest [[star]]\u2014and the only one brighter than an [[apparent magnitude]] of 4\u2014is [[Alpha Horologii]] (at 3.85), an ageing orange [[giant star]] that has swollen to around 11 times the diameter of the Sun. The [[Mira variable|long-period variable-brightness]] star, [[R Horologii]] (4.7 to 14.3), has one of the largest variations in brightness known for stars in the night sky visible to the unaided eye. Four star systems in the constellation are known to have [[exoplanet]]s; one\u2014[[Gliese 1061]]\u2014contains an exoplanet in its [[circumstellar habitable zone|habitable zone]].\n\n==History==\nThe French astronomer [[Nicolas Louis de Lacaille]] first described the [[constellation]] <!-- in French (obviously)--> as ''l'Horloge \u00e0 pendule & \u00e0 secondes'' (Clock with pendulum and seconds hand) in 1756,<ref name=ridpathlac>{{cite web |url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/lacaille.htm |title=Lacaille's Southern Planisphere of 1756 |work=Star Tales |author=Ridpath, Ian |publisher=Self-published |accessdate=19 March 2016 |author-link=Ian Ridpath |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193222/http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/lacaille.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Lacaille, Nicolas Louis |year=1756 |title=Relation abr\u00e9g\u00e9e du Voyage fait par ordre du Roi au cap de Bonne-esp\u00e9rance |journal=M\u00e9moires de l'Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Sciences |pages=519\u2013592 [588] |url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k35505/f786 |language=French |access-date=2016-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119115952/http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k35505/f786 |archive-date=2016-11-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> after he had observed and catalogued almost 10,000 southern stars during a two-year stay at the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. He devised fourteen new constellations in previously uncharted regions of the [[southern celestial hemisphere]], which were not visible from Europe. All but one honoured [[scientific instrument]]s, and so symbolised the [[Age of Enlightenment]].{{efn|1=The exception is [[Mensa (constellation)|Mensa]], named for [[Table Mountain]]. The other twelve (alongside Horologium) are [[Antlia]], [[Caelum]], [[Circinus]], [[Fornax]], [[Microscopium]], [[Norma (constellation)|Norma]], [[Octans]], [[Pictor]], [[Pyxis]], [[Reticulum]], [[Sculptor (constellation)|Sculptor]] and [[Telescopium]].<ref name=wagman/>}} The constellation name was [[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] to ''Horologium'' in a catalogue and updated chart published posthumously in 1763.<ref name=wagman>{{cite book |last=Wagman |first=Morton |date=2003 |title=Lost Stars: Lost, Missing and Troublesome Stars from the Catalogues of Johannes Bayer, Nicholas Louis de Lacaille, John Flamsteed, and Sundry Others |publisher=The McDonald & Woodward Publishing Company |location=Blacksburg, Virginia |isbn=978-0939923786 |pages=6\u20137, 169\u2013170}}</ref><!-- Cites previous three sentences --> The Latin term is ultimately derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] \u1f61\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd, for an instrument for telling the hour.<ref> {{cite web|title=horologe, noun|url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/88531#eid1280061|publisher=Oxford English Dictionary|accessdate=26 December 2019}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Horologium declension coordinates and visibility.jpg|left|thumb|Horologium constellation: showing the tangent line, or viewer's horizon, at latitude approx 23 N, which is parallel to the line of -67.04 declension, the lower declination boundary of the constellation.]]\nCovering a total of 248.9 [[square degree]]s or 0.603% of the sky, Horologium ranks 58th in area out of the 88 modern constellations.<ref name=tirionconst>{{cite web | url=http://www.ianridpath.com/constellations1.htm | title=Constellations: Andromeda\u2013Indus | work=Star Tales | author=Ridpath, Ian | publisher=self-published | accessdate=19 March 2016 | author-link=Ian Ridpath | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BScsVZIp?url=http://www.ianridpath.com/constellations1.htm | archive-date=16 October 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Its position in the southern celestial hemisphere means the whole constellation is visible to observers south of [[23rd parallel north|23\u00b0N]].<ref name=tirionconst/>{{efn|1=While parts of the constellation technically rise above the horizon to observers between the latitudes of 23\u00b0N and [[50th parallel north|50\u00b0N]], those stars within a few degrees of the horizon are difficult to see.<ref name=tirionconst/>}} Horologium is bordered by five constellations: [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]] (the [[Po (river)|Po]] river), [[Caelum]] (the [[chisel]]), [[Reticulum]] (the [[reticle]]), [[Dorado]] (the [[dolphin]]/[[swordfish]]), and [[Hydrus]] (the ''male'' [[water snake (disambiguation)|water snake]]). The three-letter abbreviation for the constellation, as adopted by the [[International Astronomical Union]] in 1922, is \"Hor\".<ref name=\"pa30_469\">{{cite journal | last=Russell | first=Henry Norris |author-link=Henry Norris Russell | title=The New International Symbols for the Constellations | journal=[[Popular Astronomy (US magazine)|Popular Astronomy]] | volume=30 | page=469 | bibcode=1922PA.....30..469R | date=1922}}</ref> The official constellation boundaries are defined by a twenty-two-sided polygon (''illustrated in infobox''). In the [[equatorial coordinate system]], the [[right ascension]] coordinates of these borders lie between {{RA|02|12.8}} and {{RA|04|20.3}}, while the [[declination]] coordinates are between \u221239.64\u00b0 and \u221267.04\u00b0.<ref name=\"boundary\">{{Cite journal | title=Horologium, Constellation Boundary | journal=The Constellations | publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]] | url=http://www.iau.org/public/constellations/#hor | accessdate=19 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605024208/http://www.iau.org/public/constellations/#hor | archive-date=5 June 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n==Features==\n[[Image:Constellation Horologium.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The constellation Horologium as it can be seen by the [[naked eye]]|alt=several scattered stars seen in evening sky]]\n\n===Stars===\n{{see also|List of stars in Horologium}}\n\nHorologium has one star brighter than [[apparent magnitude]] 4,<ref name=\"cambridge\">{{cite book|author1=Moore, Patrick |author2=Tirion, Wil |title=Cambridge Guide to Stars and Planets|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge, UK|date=1997|page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00moor/page/190 190]|isbn=978-0521585828|url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00moor|url-access=registration }}</ref> and 41 stars brighter than or equal to magnitude 6.5.{{efn|1=Objects of magnitude 6.5 are among the faintest visible to the unaided eye from locations between suburban and rural areas in [[night sky|night skies]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyandtelescope.com/resources/darksky/3304011.html?page=1&c=y |title=The Bortle Dark-Sky Scale |last=Bortle |first=John E. |date=February 2001 |work=[[Sky & Telescope]] |publisher=Sky Publishing Corporation |accessdate=1 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925104130/http://www.skyandtelescope.com/resources/darksky/3304011.html?page=1&c=y |archive-date=25 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}<ref name=\"tirionconst\"/> Lacaille charted and designated 11 stars in the constellation, giving them the [[Bayer designation]]s [[Alpha Horologii|Alpha]] (\u03b1 Hor) through [[Lambda Horologii]] (\u03bb Hor) in 1756. In the mid-19th century, English astronomer [[Francis Baily]] removed the designations of two\u2014[[HR 762|Epsilon]] and [[HR 821|Theta Horologii]]\u2014as he held they were too faint to warrant naming. He was unable to find a star that corresponded to the coordinates of Lacaille's [[Beta Horologii]]. Determining that the coordinates were wrong, he assigned the designation to another star. Kappa Horologii, too, was unable to be verified\u2014although it most likely was the star [[HD 18292]]\u2014and the name fell out of use. In 1879, American astronomer [[Benjamin Apthorp Gould]] assigned designations to what became [[Mu Horologii|Mu]] and [[Nu Horologii]] as he felt they were bright enough to warrant them.<ref name=wagman/>\n\nAt magnitude 3.9, Alpha Horologii is the brightest star in the constellation, located 115 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.5) [[light-year]]s from Earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\">{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen | title=Validation of the New Hipparcos Reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | date=2007 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 | arxiv=0708.1752}}</ref> German astronomer [[Johann Elert Bode]] depicted it as the pendulum of the clock, while Lacaille made it one of the weights.<ref name=ridphor>{{cite web | url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/horologium.htm | title=Horologium | work=Star Tales | author=Ridpath, Ian | author-link=Ian Ridpath | publisher=self-published | accessdate=21 January 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822192026/http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/horologium.htm | archive-date=22 August 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> It is an orange [[giant star]] of [[Stellar classification#Spectral types|spectral type]] K2III that has swollen to around 11 times the diameter of the Sun, having spent much of its life as a [[A-type main-sequence star|white main-sequence star]].<ref name=kaleralfa>{{cite web |last1=Kaler |first1=Jim |title=Alpha Horologii |url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/alphahor.html |website=James Kaler's Stars |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408175028/http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/alphahor.html |archive-date=8 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At an estimated 1.55 times the [[mass of the Sun]],<ref name=\"Liu 2007\">{{cite journal|author=Liu, Y. J.|author2=Zhao, G.|author3=Shi, J. R.|author4=Pietrzy\u0144ski, G.|author5=Gieren, W.|date=2007|title=The Abundances of Nearby Red Clump Giants|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=382|issue=2|pages=553\u2013566|bibcode=2007MNRAS.382..553L|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2007.11852.x|doi-access=free}}</ref> it is radiating 38 times the [[Sun's luminosity]] from its [[photosphere]] at an [[effective temperature|effective (surface) temperature]] of 5,028{{nbsp}}[[Kelvin|K]].<ref name=Mcdonald>{{cite journal|author=McDonald, I.|author2=Zijlstra, A. A.|author3=Boyer, M. L.|date=2012|title=Fundamental Parameters and Infrared Excesses of Hipparcos Stars|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=427|issue=1|pages=343\u2013357|bibcode=2012MNRAS.427..343M|arxiv = 1208.2037 |doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2966.2012.21873.x }}</ref>\n\nAt magnitude 4.93, [[Delta Horologii]] is the second-brightest star in the constellation,<ref name=kalerbeta>{{cite web |last1=Kaler |first1=Jim |title=Beta Horologii |url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/betahor.html |website=James Kaler's Stars |date=21 January 2011 |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417224118/http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/betahor.html |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and forms a wide [[Double star|optical double]] with Alpha.<ref name=arnold>{{cite book |author=Arnold, H.J.P |author2=Doherty, Paul |author3=Moore, Patrick |title=The Photographic Atlas of the Stars |publisher=CRC Press |location=Boca Raton, Florida |date=1999 |page=48 |isbn=978-0750306546 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YjcvJUfnWBAC&pg=PA48}}</ref> Delta itself is a true [[Binary star|binary]] system composed of a white main sequence star of spectral type A5V that is 1.41 times as massive as the Sun with a magnitude of 5.15 and its fainter companion of magnitude 7.29.<ref name=Eggleton2008>{{cite journal | last1=Eggleton | first1=P. P. | last2=Tokovinin | first2=A. A. | title=A Catalogue of Multiplicity among Bright Stellar Systems | journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] | volume=389 | issue=2 | pages=869\u2013879 | date=2008 | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2008.13596.x | bibcode=2008MNRAS.389..869E |arxiv = 0806.2878 }}</ref> The system is located 179 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}4) light-years from the earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n\nAt magnitude 5.0, Beta Horologii is a [[white giant]] 63 times as luminous as the Sun with an effective temperature of 8,303{{nbsp}}K.<ref name=Mcdonald/> It is 312 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}4) light-years from Earth,<ref name=GaiaDR2beta>{{cite DR2|4720282071779657600}}</ref> and has been little-studied.<ref name=kalerbeta/> Lambda Horologii is an ageing yellow-white giant star of spectral type F2III that spins around at 140{{nbsp}}km/second, and is hence mildly flattened at its poles ([[Spheroid#Oblate spheroids|oblate]]).<ref name=belle>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/s00159-012-0051-2| title = Interferometric Observations of Rapidly Rotating Stars| year = 2012| last1 = Belle | first1 = G. T. | journal = The Astronomy and Astrophysics Review| volume = 20| issue = 1| page = 51| bibcode = 2012A&ARv..20...51V|arxiv = 1204.2572 }}</ref> It is 161 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}1) light-years from Earth.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n\nWith a magnitude of 5.24,<ref name=apj800_1_5/> Nu Horologii is a white main sequence star of spectral type A2V located 169 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}1) light-years from Earth<ref name=GaiaDR2nu>{{cite DR2|4721400206385912960}}</ref> that is around 1.9 times as massive as the Sun. Estimated to be around 540 million years old, it has a [[debris disk]] that appears to have two components: an inner disk is orbiting at a distance of {{val|96|+9|\u221237|u=[[Astronomical unit|AU]]}}, while an outer disk lies {{val|410|+24|\u221296|u= AU}} from the star. The estimated mass of the disks is {{val|0.13|\u00b10.07|u=%}} the mass of the Earth.<ref name=apj800_1_5>{{cite journal| last1=Meshkat | first1=Tiffany | last2=Bailey | first2=Vanessa P. | last3=Su | first3=Kate Y. L. | last4=Kenworthy | first4=Matthew A. | last5=Mamajek | first5=Eric E. | last6=Hinz | first6=Philip M. | last7=Smith | first7=Paul S. | title=Searching for Planets in Holey Debris Disks with the Apodizing Phase Plate | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=800 | issue=1 | id=5 | date=2015 | doi=10.1088/0004-637X/800/1/5 | bibcode=2015ApJ...800....5M | arxiv=1412.5179 | page=5}}</ref>\n\nHorologium has several [[variable star]]s. [[R Horologii]] is a [[red giant]] [[Mira variable]] with one of the widest ranges in brightness known of stars in the night sky visible to the unaided eye.<ref name=privett>{{cite book|last=Privett|first=Grant|author2=Jones, Kevin|title=The Constellation Observing Atlas|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|location=New York|date=2013|page=102|isbn=978-1461476481|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uN69BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|access-date=2016-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328183439/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uN69BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|archive-date=2016-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref> It is around 1,000 light-years from Earth.<ref name=GaiaDR2r>{{cite DR2|4748477123328077696}}</ref> It has a minimum magnitude of 14.3 and a maximum magnitude of 4.7, with a period of approximately 13 months.<ref name=ridpath2017/> T and U Horologii are also Mira variables.<ref name=arnold/> The [[Astronomical Society of Southern Africa]] reported in 2003 that observations of these two stars were needed as data on their light curves was incomplete.<ref name=cooper>{{cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Tim|date=2003|title=Presidential Address: Amateur Observations \u2013 Successes and Opportunities|journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa|volume=62|pages=234\u2013240|bibcode=2003MNSSA..62..234C}}</ref> [[TW Horologii]] is a [[Semiregular variable star|semiregular variable]] red giant star that is classified as a [[carbon star]],<ref name=ridpath2017/> and is 1,370 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}70) light-years from Earth.<ref name=GaiaDR2tw>{{cite DR2|4727337637895749888}}</ref>\n\n[[Iota Horologii]] is a yellow-white dwarf star 1.23 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.12) times as massive and 1.16 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.04) times as wide as the Sun with a [[Stellar classification#Spectra types|spectral type]] of F8V,<ref name=\"Bruntt2010\">{{cite journal | title=Accurate Fundamental Parameters for 23 Bright Solar-type Stars | last1=Bruntt | first1=H. | last2=Bedding | first2=T. R. | last3=Quirion | first3=P.-O. | last4=Lo Curto | first4=G. | last5=Carrier | first5=F. | last6=Smalley | first6=B. | last7=Dall | first7=T. H. | last8=Arentoft | first8=T. | last9=Bazot | first9=M. | journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society | volume=405 | issue=3 | pages=1907\u20131923 | year=2010 | arxiv=1002.4268 | bibcode=2010MNRAS.405.1907B | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2010.16575.x }}</ref> 57 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.05) light-years from Earth.<ref name=\"Gaia DR2iota\">{{Cite Gaia DR2|4745373133284418816}}</ref> Its chemical profile, movement and age indicate it formed within the [[Hyades cluster]] but has drifted around 130 light-years away from the other members.<ref name=\"Vauclair2008\">{{cite journal | title=The Exoplanet-host Star Iota Horologii: an Evaporated Member of the Primordial Hyades Cluster | last1=Vauclair | first1=S. | last2=Laymand | first2=M. | last3=Bouchy | first3=F. | last4=Vauclair | first4=G. | last5=Hui Bon Hoa | first5=A. | last6=Charpinet | first6=S. | last7=Bazot | first7=M. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=482 | issue=2 | pages=L5\u2013L8 | year=2008 | arxiv=0803.2029v1 | bibcode=2008A&A...482L...5V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20079342 }}</ref> It has a planet at least 2.5 times as massive as Jupiter orbiting it every 307 days.<ref name=\"Zechmeister2013\">{{cite journal | title=The Planet Search Programme at the ESO CES and HARPS. IV. The Search for Jupiter Analogues around Solar-like Stars | last1=Zechmeister | first1=M. | last2=K\u00fcrster | first2=M. | last3=Endl | first3=M. | last4=Lo Curto | first4=G. | last5=Hartman | first5=H. | last6=Nilsson | first6=H. | last7=Henning | first7=T. | last8=Hatzes | first8=A. P. | last9=Cochran | first9=W. D. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=552 | at=A78 | year=2013 | bibcode=2013A&A...552A..78Z | arxiv=1211.7263 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201116551 }}</ref> [[HD 27631]] is a Sun-like star located 164 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.3) light-years from Earth<ref name=GaiaDR2HD27631>{{cite DR2|4840050395924931968}}</ref> which was found to have a planet at least 1.45 times as massive as Jupiter that takes 2,208 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}66) days (six years) to complete an orbit.<ref name=\"Marmier2013\">{{cite journal | title=The CORALIE Survey for Southern Extrasolar Planets XVII. New and Updated Long Period and Massive Planets | last1=Marmier | first1=M. | last2=S\u00e9gransan | first2=D. | last3=Udry | first3=S. | last4=Mayor | first4=M. | last5=Pepe | first5=F. | last6=Queloz | first6=D. | last7=Lovis | first7=C. | last8=Naef | first8=D. | last9=Santos | first9=N. C. | last10=Alonso | first10=R. | last11=Alves | first11=S. | last12=Berthet | first12=S. | last13=Chazelas | first13=B. | last14=Demory | first14=B.-O. | last15=Dumusque | first15=X. | last16=Eggenberger | first16=A. | last17=Figueira | first17=P. | last18=Gillon | first18=M. | last19=Hagelberg | first19=J. | last20=Lendl | first20=M. | last21=Mardling | first21=R. A. | last22=M\u00e9gevand | first22=D. | last23=Neveu | first23=M. | last24=Sahlmann | first24=J. | last25=Sosnowska | first25=D. | last26=Tewes | first26=M. | last27=Triaud | first27=A. H. M. J. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=551 | at=A90 | date=2013 | arxiv=1211.6444 | bibcode=2013A&A...551A..90M | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201219639 }}</ref> [[WASP-120]] is a yellow-white main-sequence star around 1.4 times as massive as the Sun with a spectral type of F5V that is estimated to be 2.6 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}0.5) billion years old. It has a massive planet around 4.85 times the mass of Jupiter that completes its orbit every 3.6 days, and has an estimated surface temperature of 1,880 (\u00b1{{nbsp}}70){{nbsp}}K.<ref name=\"turner\">{{Cite journal|bibcode=2016PASP..128f4401T|title=WASP-120 b, WASP-122 b, and WASP-123 b: Three Newly Discovered Planets from the WASP-South Survey|journal=Publications of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific|volume=128|issue=964|pages=064401|last1=Turner|first1=O. D|last2=Anderson|first2=D. R|last3=Collier Cameron|first3=A|last4=Delrez|first4=L|last5=Evans|first5=D. F|last6=Gillon|first6=M|last7=Hellier|first7=C|last8=Jehin|first8=E|last9=Lendl|first9=M|last10=Maxted|first10=P. F. L|last11=Pepe|first11=F|last12=Pollacco|first12=D|last13=Queloz|first13=D|last14=S\u00e9gransan|first14=D|last15=Smalley|first15=B|last16=Smith|first16=A. M. S|last17=Triaud|first17=A. H. M. J|last18=Udry|first18=S|last19=West|first19=R. G|year=2016|doi=10.1088/1538-3873/128/964/064401|arxiv=1509.02210}}</ref>\n\nWith an apparent magnitude of 13.06, [[Gliese 1061]] is a [[red dwarf]] of spectral type M5.5V that has 12% of the mass and 15% of the diameter of the Sun, and shines with only 0.17% of its [[luminosity]]. Located 12 light-years away from Earth, it is the 20th-closest single star or stellar system to the Sun. In August 2019, it was announced that it had three planets, one of which lay in its [[circumstellar habitable zone|habitable zone]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anglada-Escud\u00e9 |first=G.|last2=Reiners|first2=A.|last3=Pall\u00e9|first3=E.|last4=Ribas|first4=I.|last5=Berdi\u00f1as|first5=Z. M.|last6=L\u00f3pez|first6=C. Rodr\u00edguez|last7=Morales|first7=N.|last8=L\u00f3pez-Gonz\u00e1lez|first8=M. J.|last9=Hambsch|first9=F.-J.|date=2019-08-13|title=Red Dots: A Temperate 1.5 Earth-mass Planet in a Compact Multi-terrestrial Planet System around GJ1061|doi=10.1093/mnras/staa248|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|arxiv=1908.04717v1|volume=493|issue=1|pages=536\u2013550}}</ref>\n\n===Deep-sky objects===\n[[File:NGC 1512 and NGC 1510.jpg|thumb|right|Composite image of NGC 1512 (left) and the dwarf galaxy NGC 1510|alt=A larger spiral galaxy on left and smaller rounder galaxy on right in star field.]]\n\nHorologium is home to many deep-sky objects, including several [[globular cluster]]s. [[NGC 1261]] is a globular cluster of magnitude 8, located 53,000 light-years from Earth.<ref name=ridpath2017>{{cite book | first=Ian |last=Ridpath |first2= Wil | last2= Tirion | year=2017| title=Stars and Planets Guide | publisher= Collins | location= London | isbn=978-0-00-823927-5| page=158}}</ref> It lies 4.7 degrees north-northeast of Mu Horologii.<ref name=bakich/> The globular cluster [[Arp-Madore 1]] is the most remote known globular cluster in the [[Milky Way]] at a distance of {{convert|123.3|kpc|ly|abbr=off}} from Earth.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1093/mnras/stz171|title = Proper Motions and Dynamics of the Milky Way Globular Cluster System from Gaia DR2|journal = Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume = 484|issue = 2|pages = 2832\u20132850|year = 2019|last1 = Vasiliev|first1 = Eugene|bibcode = 2019MNRAS.484.2832V|arxiv = 1807.09775}}</ref>\n\n[[NGC 1512]] is a [[barred spiral galaxy]] 2.1 degrees west-southwest of Alpha Horologii with an apparent magnitude of 10.2.<ref name=bakich>{{cite book |title=1001 Celestial Wonders to See Before You Die: The Best Sky Objects for Star Gazers |first=Michael E. |last=Bakich |publisher=Springer |year=2010 |isbn=978-1441917775 |pages=402, 416}}</ref> About five [[arcmin]] (13.8 [[Parsec#Parsecs and kiloparsecs|kpc]]) away is the [[dwarf galaxy|dwarf]] [[lenticular galaxy]] [[NGC 1510]]. The two are in the process of a merger which has been going on for 400 million years.<ref name=Monthly400>{{cite journal |last1=Koribalski |first1=B\u00e4rbel S. |last2=L\u00f3pez-S\u00e1nchez |first2= \u00c1ngel R. |date=2009 |title=Gas Dynamics and Star Formation in the Galaxy Pair NGC 1512/1510 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |volume=400 |issue=4 |page=21 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2009.15610.x |arxiv=0908.4128|bibcode=2009MNRAS.400.1749K}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster]] is a galaxy [[supercluster]], second in size only to the [[Shapley Supercluster]] in the local universe (anything within 200 [[Parsec#Megaparsecs and gigaparsecs|mpc]] of Earth). It contains over 20 [[Abell catalogue|Abell galaxy clusters]] and covers more than 100 deg<sup>2</sup><!-- Is this the same \"degree square\" we see above? If so, it should be linked and \"degree square\" should have the abbreviation posted next to it in (parens). --> of the sky, centered roughly at equatorial coordinates \u03b1 = {{RA|03|19}}, \u03b4 = {{DEC|50|2}}.<ref name=apj130_3>{{cite journal |author1=Fleenor, Matthew C. |author2=Rose, James A. |author3=Christiansen, Wayne A. |author4=Hunstead, Richard W. |authorlink4=Richard Hunstead |author5=Johnston-Hollitt, Melanie |author6=Drinkwater, Michael J. |author7=Saunders, William | title=Large-Scale Velocity Structures in the Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=130 | issue=3 | pages=957\u2013967 |date=September 2005 | doi=10.1086/431972 | bibcode=2005AJ....130..957F |arxiv = astro-ph/0505361 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 2 sentences -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Horologium}}\n* [http://www.allthesky.com/constellations/reticulum/constell.html The Deep Photographic Guide to the Constellations: Horologium]\n* [http://astrojan.eu5.org/reticul.htm The clickable Horologium]\n* [http://www.starrynightphotos.com/constellations/fornax_phoenix.htm Starry Night Photography \u2013 Horologium Constellation]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Stars of Horologium}}\n{{navconstel}}\n{{ConstellationsByLacaille}}\n{{Christiaan Huygens}}\n\n{{Sky|03|00|00|-|60|00|00|10}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n[[Category:Horologium (constellation)| ]]\n[[Category:Southern constellations]]\n[[Category:Constellations listed by Lacaille]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: 0 million \u2192 0\u00a0million (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horologium_(constellation)"}
{"title_page": "Melinda", "text_new": "{{About|the name Melinda|the genus of flies|Melinda (fly)}}\n\n{{Infobox given name\n|name = Melinda \n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|pronunciation= \n|gender = Female\n|meaning = \n|region = \n|origin = Greek\n|related names = [[Melanie]], [[Melissa]], [[Mel (given name)|Mel]], [[Linda (name)|Linda]], [[Mindy (disambiguation)|Mindy]]\n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Melinda''' is a feminine [[given name]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe modern name ''Melinda'' is a combination of \"Mel\" with the suffix \"-inda\".<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/php/view.php?name=melinda Behind the Name: Meaning, Origin and History of the Name Melinda<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\"Mel\" can be derived from names such as [[Melanie]] meaning \"dark, black\" in [[Greek language|Greek]], or from [[Melissa]] (\u03bc\u03ad\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1) meaning \"Honeybee\" in [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]. It is also associated with the Greek word ''meli'', meaning \"honey\", and with [[Linda (name)|Linda]], from \"lind\" meaning \"gentle, soft, tender\" in the [[Germanic languages]].<ref>''The Best Baby Name Book in the Whole Wide World'' (1984) by Bruce Lansky</ref>\n\n== Pronunciation ==\nThe typical English pronunciation of Melinda is {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u026a|n|d|\u0259}}. In Hungarian however, the stress is on the first syllable: {{IPA-hu|\u02c8m\u025blind\u0252|}}.\n\n== Usage and popularity ==\nThe name Melinda is used in English and Hungarian. In the United States, its popularity peaked in 1973 at No. 72. In 1990 it was in the top 1000 names in the US, and in 2002 it was in the top 100 names in Hungary. Since its peak the popularity of the name Melinda has been gradually declining in the United States, to last be seen on the top 1000 list in 2002 at No. 932.<ref>[http://www.ssa.gov/OACT/babynames/ Popular Baby Names], Social Security Administration</ref> Variations in spelling include Melynda, Melyndah, Malinda, and Milinda.\n\n[[J\u00f3zsef Katona]], Hungarian playwright and poet, used the name Melinda first in 1815 in his legendary historical tragedy ''[[B\u00e1nk b\u00e1n]]''.\n\n[[Name days in Hungary|In Hungary]], December 2 is the [[name day]] for Melinda.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Academics===\n*[[Melinda H. Keefe]], American art restorer\n*[[Melinda Mills]], British sociologist\n*[[Melinda Takeuchi]], American art historian\n*[[Melinda Tan]], Singaporean linguist\n*[[Melinda Wortz]], American art historian\n\n===Actors===\n*[[Melinda Clarke]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Y. Cohen]], American actress\n*[[Mindy Cohn|Melinda \"Mindy\" Cohn]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Culea]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Dillon]], American actress\n*[[Melinda O. Fee]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Kinnaman]], Swedish actress\n*[[Melinda Marx]], American actress and daughter of [[Groucho Marx]]\n*[[Melinda McGraw]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Messenger]], English model and TV presenter\n*[[Melinda Mullins]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Page Hamilton]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Shankar]], Canadian actress\n*[[Melinda Sullivan]], American dancer and actress\n*[[Melinda Sward]], American actress\n*[[Malinda Williams]], American actress\n\n===Artists===\n* [[Melinda Bordelon]], American painter\n*[[Melinda Doring]], Australian costume designer\n* [[Melinda Looi]], Malaysian fashion designer\n*[[Melinda Rackham]], Australian artist\n\n===Entertainers===\n*[[Melinda Bam]] South African model and beauty pageant titleholder\n*[[Melinda Ledbetter]], wife and manager of [[Brian Wilson]]\n*[[Melinda Saxe]], American magician\n\n===Lawyers===\n* [[Melinda Haag]], former US attorney\n*[[Melinda Harmon]], US judge\n*[[Melinda Taylor]], Australian ICC lawyer\n\n===Musicians===\n*[[Melinda Caroll]], American singer\n*[[Melinda Doolittle]], American singer and ''[[American Idol]]'' contestant\n*[[Melinda Kist\u00e9t\u00e9nyi]], Hungarian organist\n*[[Melinda Maxwell]], English oboist and composer\n*[[Melinda O'Neal]], American conductor\n*[[Melinda Schneider]], Australian Country Singer\n*[[Melinda Watts]], American singer and musician\n\n===Philanthropists===\n*[[Melinda Gates]], philanthropist and wife of [[Bill Gates]]\n\n===Politicians===\n*[[Malinda Brumfield White]] (born 1967), American politician\n*[[Melinda Bush]], Illinois senator\n*[[Melinda Katz]], New York politician\n*[[Melinda MacLean]], Canadian politician\n*[[Melinda Pavey]], Australian politician\n*[[Melinda Schwegmann]], Louisiana state representative and lieutenant-governor\n*[[Melinda Smyser]], Idaho senator\n*[[Melinda Sz\u00e9ky-Sztr\u00e9mi]], Hungarian politician\n\n===Reporters===\n*[[Melinda Murphy]], American reporter\n\n===Scientists===\n* [[Melinda Estes]], American neuropathologist\n\n===Sportswomen===\n*[[Melinda Cooper]], American boxer\n*[[Melinda Copp]], Canadian swimmer\n*[[Melinda Czink]], Hungarian tennis player\n*[[Melinda Gainsford-Taylor]], Australian athlete\n*[[Melinda Geiger]], Romanian handballer\n*[[Melinda Hale]], American handball player\n*[[M\u00e9linda Hennaoui]], Algerian volleyball player\n*[[Melinda Henshaw]], New Zealand yachtswoman\n*[[Melinda Jacques]], French handball player\n*[[Melinda Kunhegyi]], Canadian figure skater\n*[[Melinda McLeod]], Australian BMX cyclist\n*[[Melinda Padovano]], American wrestler\n*[[Melinda Pastrovics]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Patyi]], Hungarian canoeist\n*[[Melinda Sun]], Australian badminton player\n*[[Melinda Szikora]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Szik]], Hungarian weightlifter\n*[[Melinda Szvorda]], Hungarian footballer\n*[[Melinda Vernon]], Australian triathlete\n*[[Melinda Vincze]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Wang]], Taiwanese figure skater\n*[[Melinda Young]], Australia basketball\n\n===Writers===\n*[[Melinda Camber Porter]], British author, poet and painter\n*[[Melinda Gebbie]], American comic author and artist\n*[[Melinda Hammond]], British romance novelist\n*[[Melinda Haynes]], American novelist\n*[[Melinda Hsu Taylor]], American TV writer and producer\n*[[Malinda Lo]], American author\n*[[Melinda Lopez]], American playwright\n*[[Melinda Metz]], American children's author\n*[[Melinda Nadj Abonji]], Hungarian writer and performance artist\n*[[Melinda Rankin]] (1811\u20131888), American missionary, teacher, and writer\n*[[Melinda Smith]], Australian poet\n*[[Melinda M. Snodgrass]], American science fiction writer\n*[[Melinda Tankard Reist]], Australian writer and social campaigner\n*[[Melinda Wagner]], American composer and Pulitzer Prize winner\n\n===Other===\n*[[Murder of Shanda Sharer#Melinda Loveless|Melinda Loveless]] tortured and burned [[Murder of Shanda Sharer|Shanda Sharer]] to death with the help of other teenage girls\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n===In film and television===\n*''[[Melinda (film)]]'', American film, 1972\n*''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'', American film, 2005\n*[[Melinda Gordon]], [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]'s character from ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''\n*Melinda from ''[[The Real World: Austin]]''\n*[[Melinda Warren]] and [[List of Charmed characters#Children of Piper Halliwell and Leo Wyatt|Melinda Halliwell]], from TV show ''[[Charmed]]''\n*[[Melinda Warner]], [[Medical examiner]] on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n*Melinda Cramer, [[One Life to Live characters (1968\u201379)|character]] on ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n*Melinda May from ''[[Marvel's Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n*Melinda, a centaur from the Disney movie ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]''\n\n===In music===\n*\"Sweet Melinda, the peasants call her the Goddess of Gloom\" from ''[[Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues]]'' by Bob Dylan, 1965\n*\"I can't stay much longer,  Melinda, the sun is getting high.\" Cumberland Blues. Lyrics by [[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]], performed by the [[Grateful Dead]].\n*Melinda, one of the two main characters in the story of [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Death metal#Progressive death metal|progressive death metal]] band [[Opeth]]'s 1999 concept album ''[[Still Life (Opeth album)|Still Life]]'', which includes the song \"Face of Melinda\"\n*\"Sweet Dreams, Melinda\" by [[Trey Anastasio]] on the album ''[[Shine (Trey Anastasio album)|Shine]]''\n*\"Sweet Melinda\" by [[John Denver]] on the album ''John Denver''\n*\"[[Come Away Melinda]]\", written by [[Fred Hellerman]] and [[Fran Minkoff]], and recorded by [[Harry Belafonte]] (on the album ''[[Streets I Have Walked]]''), [[Judy Collins]] (''[[Judy Collins 3]]''), [[Theodore Bikel]] (''A Folksinger's Choice''), [[Tim Rose]] (''Tim Rose''), [[Bobbie Gentry]] (''[[Local Gentry]]''), [[Uriah Heep (band)|Uriah Heep]] (''[[...Very 'Eavy ...Very 'Umble]]''), [[Velvett Fogg]]), [[Kenny Rankin]] (''Mind-Dusters''), [[Tim Rose|The Big 3]] (''Live at the Recording Studio''), and [[L.Stadt]].\n*\"Me and My Melinda\" by [[Kay Kyser]]\n*\"Remember Melinda\" by [[TQ (singer)|TQ]] on the album ''[[They Never Saw Me Coming]]''\n*\"Melinda was mine...\" from ''[[Solitary Man (song)|Solitary Man]]'' by [[Neil Diamond]]\n*\"Melinda\" by [[Curved Air]] appears on the album ''Retrospective''\n*\"Melinda\" by [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]]\n\n===In literature===\n*Melinda, wife of B\u00e1nk in [[J\u00f3zsef Katona]]'s legendary historical tragedy ''[[B\u00e1nk b\u00e1n]]''\n*Melinda (\"Lindy\") in the book ''[[The Last of the Really Great Whangdoodles]]'' by [[Julie Andrews]]\n*[[Melinda Sordino]], main character of the book ''[[Speak (Anderson novel)|Speak]]'' (1999) by [[Laurie Halse Anderson]]\n*Melinda, porn star mentioned in the book ''[[Snow (Pamuk novel)|Snow]]'' by [[Orhan Pamuk]]\n*Melinda, picture book written by [[Neil Gaiman]] and illustrated by Dagmara Matusak\n\n===In agriculture===\n*[[:it:Melinda|Melinda]] is a consortium producing apples in [[Trentino]].\n\n===In geography===\n* [[Melinda Airport]] in [[Belize]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{lookfrom|Melinda}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:Feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Hungarian feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the name Melinda|the genus of flies|Melinda (fly)}}\n\n{{Infobox given name\n|name = Melinda \n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|pronunciation= \n|gender = Female\n|meaning = \n|region = \n|origin = Greek\n|related names = [[Melanie]], [[Melissa]], [[Mel (given name)|Mel]], [[Linda (name)|Linda]], [[Mindy (disambiguation)|Mindy]]\n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Melinda''' is a feminine [[given name]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe modern name ''Melinda'' is a combination of \"Mel\" with the suffix \"-inda\".<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/php/view.php?name=melinda Behind the Name: Meaning, Origin and History of the Name Melinda<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\"Mel\" can be derived from names such as [[Melanie]] meaning \"dark, black\" in [[Greek language|Greek]], or from [[Melissa]] (\u03bc\u03ad\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1) meaning \"Honeybee\" in [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]. It is also associated with the Greek word ''meli'', meaning \"honey\", and with [[Linda (name)|Linda]], from \"lind\" meaning \"gentle, soft, tender\" in the [[Germanic languages]].<ref>''The Best Baby Name Book in the Whole Wide World'' (1984) by Bruce Lansky</ref>\n\n== Pronunciation ==\nThe typical English pronunciation of Melinda is {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u026a|n|d|\u0259}}. In Hungarian however, the stress is on the first syllable: {{IPA-hu|\u02c8m\u025blind\u0252|}}.\n\n== Usage and popularity ==\nThe name Melinda is used in English and Hungarian. In the United States, its popularity peaked in 1973 at No. 72. In 1990 it was in the top 1000 names in the US, and in 2002 it was in the top 100 names in Hungary. Since its peak the popularity of the name Melinda has been gradually declining in the United States, to last be seen on the top 1000 list in 2002 at No. 932.<ref>[http://www.ssa.gov/OACT/babynames/ Popular Baby Names], Social Security Administration</ref> Variations in spelling include Melynda, Melyndah, Malinda, and Milinda.\n\n[[J\u00f3zsef Katona]], Hungarian playwright and poet, used the name Melinda first in 1815 in his legendary historical tragedy ''[[B\u00e1nk b\u00e1n]]''.\n\n[[Name days in Hungary|In Hungary]], December 2 is the [[name day]] for Melinda.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Academics===\n*[[Melinda H. Keefe]], American art restorer\n*[[Melinda Mills]], British sociologist\n*[[Melinda Takeuchi]], American art historian\n*[[Melinda Tan]], Singaporean linguist\n*[[Melinda Wortz]], American art historian\n\n===Actors===\n*[[Melinda Clarke]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Y. Cohen]], American actress\n*[[Mindy Cohn|Melinda \"Mindy\" Cohn]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Culea]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Dillon]], American actress\n*[[Melinda O. Fee]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Kinnaman]], Swedish actress\n*[[Melinda Marx]], American actress and daughter of [[Groucho Marx]]\n*[[Melinda McGraw]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Messenger]], English model and TV presenter\n*[[Melinda Mullins]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Page Hamilton]], American actress\n*[[Melinda Shankar]], Canadian actress\n*[[Melinda Sullivan]], American dancer and actress\n*[[Melinda Sward]], American actress\n*[[Malinda Williams]], American actress\n\n===Artists===\n* [[Melinda Bordelon]], American painter\n*[[Melinda Doring]], Australian costume designer\n* [[Melinda Looi]], Malaysian fashion designer\n*[[Melinda Rackham]], Australian artist\n\n===Entertainers===\n*[[Melinda Bam]] South African model and beauty pageant titleholder\n*[[Melinda Ledbetter]], wife and manager of [[Brian Wilson]]\n*[[Melinda Saxe]], American magician\n\n===Lawyers===\n* [[Melinda Haag]], former US attorney\n*[[Melinda Harmon]], US judge\n*[[Melinda Taylor]], Australian ICC lawyer\n\n===Musicians===\n*[[Melinda Caroll]], American singer\n*[[Melinda Doolittle]], American singer and ''[[American Idol]]'' contestant\n*[[Melinda Kist\u00e9t\u00e9nyi]], Hungarian organist\n*[[Melinda Maxwell]], English oboist and composer\n*[[Melinda O'Neal]], American conductor\n*[[Melinda Schneider]], Australian Country Singer\n*[[Melinda Watts]], American singer and musician\n\n===Philanthropists===\n*[[Melinda Gates]], philanthropist and wife of [[Bill Gates]]\n\n===Politicians===\n*[[Malinda Brumfield White]] (born 1967), American politician\n*[[Melinda Bush]], Illinois senator\n*[[Melinda Katz]], New York politician\n*[[Melinda MacLean]], Canadian politician\n*[[Melinda Pavey]], Australian politician\n*[[Melinda Schwegmann]], Louisiana state representative and lieutenant-governor\n*[[Melinda Smyser]], Idaho senator\n*[[Melinda Sz\u00e9ky-Sztr\u00e9mi]], Hungarian politician\n\n===Reporters===\n*[[Melinda Murphy]], American reporter\n\n===Scientists===\n* [[Melinda Estes]], American neuropathologist\n\n===Sportswomen===\n*[[Melinda Cooper]], American boxer\n*[[Melinda Copp]], Canadian swimmer\n*[[Melinda Czink]], Hungarian tennis player\n*[[Melinda Gainsford-Taylor]], Australian athlete\n*[[Melinda Geiger]], Romanian handballer\n*[[Melinda Hale]], American handball player\n*[[M\u00e9linda Hennaoui]], Algerian volleyball player\n*[[Melinda Henshaw]], New Zealand yachtswoman\n*[[Melinda Jacques]], French handball player\n*[[Melinda Kunhegyi]], Canadian figure skater\n*[[Melinda McLeod]], Australian BMX cyclist\n*[[Melinda Padovano]], American wrestler\n*[[Melinda Pastrovics]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Patyi]], Hungarian canoeist\n*[[Melinda Sun]], Australian badminton player\n*[[Melinda Szikora]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Szik]], Hungarian weightlifter\n*[[Melinda Szvorda]], Hungarian footballer\n*[[Melinda Vernon]], Australian triathlete\n*[[Melinda Vincze]], Hungarian handballer\n*[[Melinda Wang]], Taiwanese figure skater\n*[[Melinda Young]], Australia basketball\n\n===Writers===\n*[[Melinda Camber Porter]], British author, poet and painter\n*[[Melinda Gebbie]], American comic author and artist\n*[[Melinda Hammond]], British romance novelist\n*[[Melinda Haynes]], American novelist\n*[[Melinda Hsu Taylor]], American TV writer and producer\n*[[Malinda Lo]], American author\n*[[Melinda Lopez]], American playwright\n*[[Melinda Metz]], American children's author\n*[[Melinda Nadj Abonji]], Hungarian writer and performance artist\n*[[Melinda Rankin]] (1811\u20131888), American missionary, teacher, and writer\n*[[Melinda Smith]], Australian poet\n*[[Melinda M. Snodgrass]], American science fiction writer\n*[[Melinda Tankard Reist]], Australian writer and social campaigner\n*[[Melinda Wagner]], American composer and Pulitzer Prize winner\n\n===Other===\n*[[Murder of Shanda Sharer#Melinda Loveless|Melinda Loveless]] tortured and burned [[Murder of Shanda Sharer|Shanda Sharer]] to death with the help of other teenage girls\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n===In film and television===\n*''[[Melinda (film)]]'', American film, 1972\n*''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'', American film, 2005\n*[[Melinda Gordon]], [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]'s character from ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''\n*Melinda from ''[[The Real World: Austin]]''\n*[[Melinda Warren]] and [[List of Charmed characters#Children of Piper Halliwell and Leo Wyatt|Melinda Halliwell]], from TV show ''[[Charmed]]''\n*[[Melinda Warner]], [[Medical examiner]] on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n*Melinda Cramer, [[One Life to Live characters (1968\u201379)|character]] on ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n*Melinda May from ''[[Marvel's Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n*Melinda, a centaur from the Disney movie ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]''\n\n===In music===\n*\"Sweet Melinda, the peasants call her the Goddess of Gloom\" from ''[[Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues]]'' by Bob Dylan, 1965\n*\"I can't stay much longer,  Melinda, the sun is getting high.\" Cumberland Blues. Lyrics by [[Robert Hunter]], performed by the [[Grateful Dead]].\n*Melinda, one of the two main characters in the story of [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Death metal#Progressive death metal|progressive death metal]] band [[Opeth]]'s 1999 concept album ''[[Still Life (Opeth album