minine given names]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobert Hunter(link changed toRobert Hunter (lyricist)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melinda"}
{"title_page": "Unsinkable Sam", "text_new": "{{short description|Nickname of a cat, reportedly in service as a ship's cat during World War II}}\n{{Infobox animal\n| name                    = Oscar<br>Unsinkable Sam\n| image                   = \n| image_upright           = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_name              = yes\n| othername               = \n| species                 = [[Cat]]\n| breed                   = \n| gender                  = \n| birth_date              = Before 1941\n| birth_place             = [[Nazi Germany]]\n| death_date              = 1955\n| death_place             = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| resting_place           = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality             = \n| occupation              = \n| employer                = {{plainlist|\n*''[[Kriegsmarine]]''\n*[[Royal Navy]]}}\n| role                    = [[Ship's cat]]\n| years_active            =1941\u20131946 \n| known                   = \n| tricks                  = \n| awards                  = \n| title                   = \n| term                    = \n| predecessor             = \n| successor               = \n| owner                   = \n| residence               = \n| parents                 = \n| children                = yee\n| weight                  = \n| height                  = \n| appearance              = \n| namedafter              = \n| website                 = \n}}\n{{external media| align  =right | width  =220px | image1 = [http://www.ww2incolor.com/art/SamGeorfinaShawBakerGreenwich.html ''Unsinkable Sam aka Oskar''], drawing at UK National Maritime Museum, Greenwich}}\n\n'''Unsinkable Sam''' (also known as '''Oskar''' or '''Oscar''') is the apocryphal nickname of a [[ship's cat]] who purportedly served during [[World War II]] with both the [[Kriegsmarine]] and the [[Royal Navy]] and survived the sinking of three ships.\n\n==History==\nThe cat's original name is unknown.  The name \"Oscar\" was given by the crew of the  British destroyer [[HMS Cossack (F03)|HMS ''Cossack'']] that rescued him from the sea following the sinking of the German battleship  [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']].  \"Oscar\" was derived from the [[International Code of Signals]] for the letter 'O', which is code for \"[[Man overboard|Man '''O'''verboard]]\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Butkus|first1=Venantas|title=The fame of ships' cats|url=http://jura.diena.lt/en/news/other/the-fame-of-ships-cats-362825|website=jura.diena.lt|accessdate=25 June 2017|date=8 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130314/http://jura.diena.lt/en/news/other/the-fame-of-ships-cats-362825|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> (the German spelling, \"Oskar\", was sometimes used since he was a German cat).\n\n===''Bismarck''===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 193-04-1-26, Schlachtschiff Bismarck.jpg|thumb|''Bismarck'']]\n\nThe black and white patched cat was supposedly owned by an unknown crewman of the German battleship [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']] <ref name=\"100 cats\">\n{{citation\n| first = Sam | last = Stall\n| title = 100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines\n| pages = 57\u201358\n| publisher = Quirk Books\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=coXIF8WbEKEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| year = 2007\n| isbn = 978-1-59474-163-0}}\n</ref> and was on board the ship on 18 May 1941 when she set sail on [[Operation Rhein\u00fcbung |Operation ''Rhein\u00fcbung'']] (German for  Rhine Exercise), ''Bismarck''{{'}}s only mission. ''Bismarck'' was [[Last battle of the battleship Bismarck|sunk after a fierce sea-battle]] on 27 May, from which only 115 from her crew of over 2,100 survived. Hours later, Oscar was found floating on a board and picked from the water by the British destroyer [[HMS Cossack (F03)|HMS ''Cossack'']].<ref name=pie>{{cite book|last1=Pieka\u0142kiewicz|first1=Janusz|title=Sea War 1939-1945|date=1987|publisher=Blandford|isbn=0713716657|oclc=15197891|language=English}}</ref>{{rp|142}} Unaware of what his name had been on ''Bismarck'', the crew of ''Cossack'' named their new mascot \"Oscar\".<ref name=pie/>{{rp|142}}\n\n===HMS ''Cossack''===\n[[File:HMS Cossack.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Cossack'']]\n\nThe cat served on board ''Cossack'' for the next few months as the ship carried out convoy escort duties in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and north [[Atlantic Ocean]]. On 24 October 1941, ''Cossack'' was escorting a convoy from [[Gibraltar]] to [[Great Britain]] when she was severely damaged by a [[torpedo]] fired by the {{GS|U-563||6}}.<ref name=pie/>{{rp|170}} Crew were transferred to the destroyer {{HMS|Legion|G74|6}}, and an attempt was made to tow the badly listing ''Cossack'' back to Gibraltar. However, worsening weather conditions meant the task became impossible and had to be abandoned. On 27 October, a day after the tow was slipped, ''Cossack'' sank to the west of Gibraltar. The initial explosion had blown off one third of the forward section of the ship, killing 159 of the crew, but Oscar survived this too and was brought to the shore establishment in Gibraltar.<ref name=pie/>{{rp|170}}\n\n===HMS ''Ark Royal''===\n[[File:HMS Ark Royal sinking.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Ark Royal'' sinking]]\n\nNow nicknamed \"Unsinkable Sam\", the cat was soon transferred to the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Ark Royal|91|6}}, which coincidentally had been instrumental in the destruction of ''Bismarck'' (along with ''Cossack''). However, Sam was to find no more luck there, and when returning from [[Malta]] on 14 November 1941 this ship too was torpedoed, this time by {{GS|U-81|1941|2}}. Attempts were also made to tow ''Ark Royal'' to Gibraltar, but the unstoppable inflow of water made the task futile. The carrier rolled over and sank 30 miles from Gibraltar. The slow rate at which the ship sank meant that all but one of the crew could be saved. The survivors, including Sam, who had been found clinging to a floating plank by a [[Motor Launch]]<ref name=iwm>\n{{citation\n| author = Imperial War Museum\n| title = The Animals' War: Special Exhibitions Gallery\n| url = http://archive.iwm.org.uk/upload/package/74/AnimalsWar/images/AnimalsWarObjects.pdf\n| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2016}}\n</ref> and described as \"angry but quite unharmed\",<ref name=Jameson>\n{{citation\n| first = William | last = Jameson\n| title = Ark Royal: The Life of an Aircraft Carrier at War 1939-41\n| page = 348\n| year = 2004\n| publisher = Periscope Publishing\n| isbn = 1-904381-27-8}}\n</ref> were transferred to [[HMS Lightning (G55)|HMS ''Lightning'']]<ref> Dann,John & Gilroy Eric, ''Struck by Lightning'', (2012), Story of HMS Lightning 1941-43 {{ISBN|978-178035-480-4}} </ref> and the same [[HMS Legion (G74)|HMS ''Legion'']] which had rescued the crew of ''Cossack''. ''Legion'' would itself be sunk in 1942, and ''Lightning'' in 1943.\n\nThe loss of ''Ark Royal'' proved the end of Sam's shipborne career. He was transferred first to the offices of the [[Governor of Gibraltar]] and then sent back to the United Kingdom, where he saw out the remainder of the war living in a seaman's home in [[Belfast]] called the \"Home for Sailors\".<ref name=pie/>{{rp|173}} Sam died in 1955.<ref> Stall, Sam (2007), 100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines, Quirk Books, pp. 57\u201358, {{ISBN|1-59474-163-8}} </ref> A pastel portrait of Sam (titled ''Oscar, the Bismarck's Cat'') by the artist Georgina Shaw-Baker is in the possession of the [[National Maritime Museum]] in Greenwich.<ref name=iwm/>\n\n==Historicity==\n{{Anchor|Existence}}\nSome authorities question whether Oskar/Sam's biography might be a \"[[Nautical fiction|sea story]]\", because \u2013 for example \u2013 there are pictures of two different cats identified as Oskar/Sam. The sinking of ''Bismarck'' and rescue of a limited number of survivors took place in desperate conditions; British ships were ordered not to stop as there was believed to be a [[U-boat]] in the area, and many survivors were left to die of exposure. Pointedly, there is no mention of this incident in [[Ludovic Kennedy]]'s detailed account of the sinking,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=Ludovic|title=Pursuit: The Chase and Sinking of the Bismarck|date=2001|publisher=Cassell & Co|isbn=0304355267|oclc=45828404|language=English}}</ref> suggesting that information later gleaned from sailors regarding the cat's true service were [[wiktionary:apocryphal|apocryphal]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baker|first1=Georgina Shaw|title=Item #PAJ2744: ''Oscar, Cat From the German Battleship Bismarck'' \u2013 Private Collections of the National Maritime Museum|url=http://collections.rmg.co.uk/collections/objects/203480.html|website=Royal Museums Greenwich|location=London, UK|format=Framed drawing in pastel, 785 \u00d7 610 mm|quote=Some doubt has been cast on Oscar's origins on the ''Bismarck'' both for practical reasons, including there being no survivor account of him there, and because two contradictory photos exist.}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book\n| first = Val \n| last = Lewis\n| title = Ships' Cats in War and Peace\n| publisher = Nauticalia\n| location=Shepperton\n| year = 2001\n| isbn = 978-0-9530458-1-5}}\n* {{cite web\n| first = Laura | last = Vocelle\n| title = Cats in 20th Century History (Cats in War-Unsinkable Sam)\n| url = http://www.thegreatcat.org/cats-in-20th-century-history-cats-in-war-unsinkable-sam/|website=thegreatcat.org}}\n\n[[Category:1955 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:German battleship Bismarck]]\n[[Category:Individual cats]]\n[[Category:Military animals of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nickname of a cat, reportedly in service as a ship's cat during World War II}}\n{{Infobox animal\n| name                    = Oscar<br>Unsinkable Sam\n| image                   = \n| image_upright           = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_name              = \n| othername               = \n| species                 = [[Cat]]\n| breed                   = \n| gender                  = \n| birth_date              = Before 1941\n| birth_place             = [[Nazi Germany]]\n| death_date              = 1955\n| death_place             = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| resting_place           = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality             = \n| occupation              = \n| employer                = {{plainlist|\n*''[[Kriegsmarine]]''\n*[[Royal Navy]]}}\n| role                    = [[Ship's cat]]\n| years_active            =1941\u20131946 \n| known                   = \n| tricks                  = \n| awards                  = \n| title                   = \n| term                    = \n| predecessor             = \n| successor               = \n| owner                   = \n| residence               = \n| parents                 = \n| children                = \n| weight                  = \n| height                  = \n| appearance              = \n| namedafter              = \n| website                 = \n}}\n{{external media| align  =right | width  =220px | image1 = [http://www.ww2incolor.com/art/SamGeorfinaShawBakerGreenwich.html ''Unsinkable Sam aka Oskar''], drawing at UK National Maritime Museum, Greenwich}}\n\n'''Unsinkable Sam''' (also known as '''Oskar''' or '''Oscar''') is the apocryphal nickname of a [[ship's cat]] who purportedly served during [[World War II]] with both the [[Kriegsmarine]] and the [[Royal Navy]] and survived the sinking of three ships.\n\n==History==\nThe cat's original name is unknown.  The name \"Oscar\" was given by the crew of the  British destroyer [[HMS Cossack (F03)|HMS ''Cossack'']] that rescued him from the sea following the sinking of the German battleship  [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']].  \"Oscar\" was derived from the [[International Code of Signals]] for the letter 'O', which is code for \"[[Man overboard|Man '''O'''verboard]]\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Butkus|first1=Venantas|title=The fame of ships' cats|url=http://jura.diena.lt/en/news/other/the-fame-of-ships-cats-362825|website=jura.diena.lt|accessdate=25 June 2017|date=8 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130314/http://jura.diena.lt/en/news/other/the-fame-of-ships-cats-362825|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> (the German spelling, \"Oskar\", was sometimes used since he was a German cat).\n\n===''Bismarck''===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 193-04-1-26, Schlachtschiff Bismarck.jpg|thumb|''Bismarck'']]\n\nThe black and white patched cat was supposedly owned by an unknown crewman of the German battleship [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']] <ref name=\"100 cats\">\n{{citation\n| first = Sam | last = Stall\n| title = 100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines\n| pages = 57\u201358\n| publisher = Quirk Books\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=coXIF8WbEKEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| year = 2007\n| isbn = 978-1-59474-163-0}}\n</ref> and was on board the ship on 18 May 1941 when she set sail on [[Operation Rhein\u00fcbung |Operation ''Rhein\u00fcbung'']] (German for  Rhine Exercise), ''Bismarck''{{'}}s only mission. ''Bismarck'' was [[Last battle of the battleship Bismarck|sunk after a fierce sea-battle]] on 27 May, from which only 115 from her crew of over 2,100 survived. Hours later, Oscar was found floating on a board and picked from the water by the British destroyer [[HMS Cossack (F03)|HMS ''Cossack'']].<ref name=pie>{{cite book|last1=Pieka\u0142kiewicz|first1=Janusz|title=Sea War 1939-1945|date=1987|publisher=Blandford|isbn=0713716657|oclc=15197891|language=English}}</ref>{{rp|142}} Unaware of what his name had been on ''Bismarck'', the crew of ''Cossack'' named their new mascot \"Oscar\".<ref name=pie/>{{rp|142}}\n\n===HMS ''Cossack''===\n[[File:HMS Cossack.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Cossack'']]\n\nThe cat served on board ''Cossack'' for the next few months as the ship carried out convoy escort duties in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and north [[Atlantic Ocean]]. On 24 October 1941, ''Cossack'' was escorting a convoy from [[Gibraltar]] to [[Great Britain]] when she was severely damaged by a [[torpedo]] fired by the {{GS|U-563||6}}.<ref name=pie/>{{rp|170}} Crew were transferred to the destroyer {{HMS|Legion|G74|6}}, and an attempt was made to tow the badly listing ''Cossack'' back to Gibraltar. However, worsening weather conditions meant the task became impossible and had to be abandoned. On 27 October, a day after the tow was slipped, ''Cossack'' sank to the west of Gibraltar. The initial explosion had blown off one third of the forward section of the ship, killing 159 of the crew, but Oscar survived this too and was brought to the shore establishment in Gibraltar.<ref name=pie/>{{rp|170}}\n\n===HMS ''Ark Royal''===\n[[File:HMS Ark Royal sinking.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Ark Royal'' sinking]]\n\nNow nicknamed \"Unsinkable Sam\", the cat was soon transferred to the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Ark Royal|91|6}}, which coincidentally had been instrumental in the destruction of ''Bismarck'' (along with ''Cossack''). However, Sam was to find no more luck there, and when returning from [[Malta]] on 14 November 1941 this ship too was torpedoed, this time by {{GS|U-81|1941|2}}. Attempts were also made to tow ''Ark Royal'' to Gibraltar, but the unstoppable inflow of water made the task futile. The carrier rolled over and sank 30 miles from Gibraltar. The slow rate at which the ship sank meant that all but one of the crew could be saved. The survivors, including Sam, who had been found clinging to a floating plank by a [[Motor Launch]]<ref name=iwm>\n{{citation\n| author = Imperial War Museum\n| title = The Animals' War: Special Exhibitions Gallery\n| url = http://archive.iwm.org.uk/upload/package/74/AnimalsWar/images/AnimalsWarObjects.pdf\n| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2016}}\n</ref> and described as \"angry but quite unharmed\",<ref name=Jameson>\n{{citation\n| first = William | last = Jameson\n| title = Ark Royal: The Life of an Aircraft Carrier at War 1939-41\n| page = 348\n| year = 2004\n| publisher = Periscope Publishing\n| isbn = 1-904381-27-8}}\n</ref> were transferred to [[HMS Lightning (G55)|HMS ''Lightning'']]<ref> Dann,John & Gilroy Eric, ''Struck by Lightning'', (2012), Story of HMS Lightning 1941-43 {{ISBN|978-178035-480-4}} </ref> and the same [[HMS Legion (G74)|HMS ''Legion'']] which had rescued the crew of ''Cossack''. ''Legion'' would itself be sunk in 1942, and ''Lightning'' in 1943.\n\nThe loss of ''Ark Royal'' proved the end of Sam's shipborne career. He was transferred first to the offices of the [[Governor of Gibraltar]] and then sent back to the United Kingdom, where he saw out the remainder of the war living in a seaman's home in [[Belfast]] called the \"Home for Sailors\".<ref name=pie/>{{rp|173}} Sam died in 1955.<ref> Stall, Sam (2007), 100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines, Quirk Books, pp. 57\u201358, {{ISBN|1-59474-163-8}} </ref> A pastel portrait of Sam (titled ''Oscar, the Bismarck's Cat'') by the artist Georgina Shaw-Baker is in the possession of the [[National Maritime Museum]] in Greenwich.<ref name=iwm/>\n\n==Historicity==\n{{Anchor|Existence}}\nSome authorities question whether Oskar/Sam's biography might be a \"[[Nautical fiction|sea story]]\", because \u2013 for example \u2013 there are pictures of two different cats identified as Oskar/Sam. The sinking of ''Bismarck'' and rescue of a limited number of survivors took place in desperate conditions; British ships were ordered not to stop as there was believed to be a [[U-boat]] in the area, and many survivors were left to die of exposure. Pointedly, there is no mention of this incident in [[Ludovic Kennedy]]'s detailed account of the sinking,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=Ludovic|title=Pursuit: The Chase and Sinking of the Bismarck|date=2001|publisher=Cassell & Co|isbn=0304355267|oclc=45828404|language=English}}</ref> suggesting that information later gleaned from sailors regarding the cat's true service were [[wiktionary:apocryphal|apocryphal]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baker|first1=Georgina Shaw|title=Item #PAJ2744: ''Oscar, Cat From the German Battleship Bismarck'' \u2013 Private Collections of the National Maritime Museum|url=http://collections.rmg.co.uk/collections/objects/203480.html|website=Royal Museums Greenwich|location=London, UK|format=Framed drawing in pastel, 785 \u00d7 610 mm|quote=Some doubt has been cast on Oscar's origins on the ''Bismarck'' both for practical reasons, including there being no survivor account of him there, and because two contradictory photos exist.}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book\n| first = Val \n| last = Lewis\n| title = Ships' Cats in War and Peace\n| publisher = Nauticalia\n| location=Shepperton\n| year = 2001\n| isbn = 978-0-9530458-1-5}}\n* {{cite web\n| first = Laura | last = Vocelle\n| title = Cats in 20th Century History (Cats in War-Unsinkable Sam)\n| url = http://www.thegreatcat.org/cats-in-20th-century-history-cats-in-war-unsinkable-sam/|website=thegreatcat.org}}\n\n[[Category:1955 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:German battleship Bismarck]]\n[[Category:Individual cats]]\n[[Category:Military animals of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "2601:645:680:650:1108:97ca:d279:f879", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsinkable_Sam"}
{"title_page": "Daniel M. Pierce", "text_new": "{{short description|American lawyer}}\n{{for|the fictional character|Perception (U.S. TV series)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Daniel Pierce\n|image           = \n|alt             = \n|office          = Mayor of [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|term_start      = 1999 \n|term_end        = 2003\n|predecessor     = [[Raymond Geraci]]\n|successor       = [[Michael Belsky]]\n|term_start2     = 1987\n|term_end2       = April 24, 1995\n|predecessor2    = ?\n|successor2      = [[Raymond Geraci]]\n|office3         = Member of the<br>[[Illinois House of Representatives]]<br>from the 58th district<br>{{small|32nd district (1967-1983); At large (1965-1967)}}\n|term_start3     = 1965\n|term_end3       = 1985\n|predecessor3    = ''At large district created''\n|successor3      = [[Grace Mary Stern]]\n<!-- personal -->\n|birth_name      = Daniel Marshall Pierce\n|birth_date      = {{Birth date|1928|3|31}}\n|birth_place     = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|death_date      =  {{Death date and age|2020|2|13|1928|3|31}}\n|death_place     = [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|death_cause     = \n|resting_place   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|citizenship     = \n|nationality     = \n|party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse          = Rhoda\n|children        = \n|residence       = [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|alma_mater      = {{nowrap| [[Harvard College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])}}<br>[[Harvard Law School]] {{small|([[Juris doctor|J.D.]])}}}}\n|occupation      = \n|profession      = Attorney\n<!-- militaryservice -->\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Air Force}}\n|serviceyears = \n|rank         = \n|unit         = {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force Judge Advocate General's Corps|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Marshall Pierce''' (March 31, 1928 \u2013 February 13, 2020) was an American lawyer and politician from [[Illinois]]. He served as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]], as Mayor of [[Highland Park, Illinois]], and as a trustee on the North Shore Water Reclamation District.\n\n==Early life==\nPierce was born March 31, 1928 in Chicago. His family moved to the [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] where he graduated from [[New Trier High School]]. He earned degrees from [[Harvard College]] and [[Harvard Law School]]. He served in the [[United States Air Force Judge Advocate General's Corps]] during the [[Korean War]]. While in the Air Force, he attended the [[Air Command and Staff College|United States Air Force Command & Staff School]]. He then took a position with Altheimer, Gray, Naiburg, Strasburger & Lawton where he would remain for the remainder of his legal career.<ref name=\"Blue Book 1967-1968\">{{cite book|author=<!--staff writer-->|title=Illinois Blue Book 1967-1968|page=255|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|url= http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/ref/collection/bb/id/20934|year=1968|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"2003 Resolution\" />\n\n==Illinois House of Representatives==\nIn an unusual election, Pierce ran on a statewide ballot after the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] ordered an at large election for all 177 members of the Illinois House; the result of partisan gridlock preventing the completion of the decennial reapportionment process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1194.html|title=State Politics|last=Devine|first=Michael J.|year=2005|journal=Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 1965 Illinois Supreme Court Case to resolve the redistricting issue, Pierce's [[Highland Park, Illinois|Highland Park]] home was drawn into the 32nd district which consisted of [[Algonquin Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Algonquin]], [[Dorr Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Dorr]],\n[[Grafton Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Grafton]], and [[Nunda Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Nunda]] townships in [[McHenry County, Illinois|McHenry County]] and [[Cuba Township, Lake County, Illinois|Cuba]], [[Deerfield Township, Lake County, Illinois|Deerfield]], [[Ela Township, Lake County, Illinois|Ela]], [[Fremont Township, Lake County, Illinois|Fremont]], [[Libertyville Township, Lake County, Illinois|Libertyville]],\n[[Shields Township, Lake County, Illinois|Shields]], [[Vernon Township, Lake County, Illinois|Vernon]], [[Wauconda Township, Lake County, Illinois|Wauconda]] and [[West Deerfield Township, Lake County, Illinois|West Deerfield]] townships in [[Lake County, Illinois|Lake County]]. He was reelected as one of the district's three representatives.<ref>{{cite book|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Illinois Blue Book 1967-1968|chapter=Representative Reapportionment: Legal Descriptions for Cook County Representative Districts Other Than Cook County|url=http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/ref/collection/bb/id/20934|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|page=255 & 327|date=|isbn=}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure, he was a member of the Democratic Study Group, a caucus of independent, liberal Democrats. His role in this organization earned him a nominal spot on the leadership team of then-Minority Leader [[Clyde L. Choate]].<ref name=JAFFE>{{cite book|last=Barber|first=Charles M.|title=Judge Aaron Jaffe: Reforming Illinois: A Progressive Tackles State Government|publisher=[[AuthorHouse]]|location=[[Bloomington, Indiana]]|date=April 4, 2016|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=150498384X|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref> Pierce served as a delegate for [[Edmund Muskie]] in the [[1972 United States presidential election|1972 Democratic presidential primary]].<ref name=JAFFE /> He was in favor of the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=<!--none-->|title=Downstate candidates for Illinois House|magazine=Illinois Issues|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=October 1978|page=11}}</ref> He  served as Chairman of the House Revenue Committee, the Mental Health Investigating  Committee,  the  Energy  and Environment   Committee,   the   Illinois   Economic   Fiscal Commission,  and  the  Energy  Resources  Commission He served on the House Public Utilities Committee and as House  Minority  Whip  for  two terms.<ref name=\"2003 Resolution\" />\n\nPierce explored running for the Democratic nomination for [[Illinois Attorney General]] in the 1982 primary, but stepped aside after failing to be slated by the Cook County Democratic Party in favor of [[Neil Hartigan]]. Hartigan would go on to beat incumbent [[Tyrone C. Fahner]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kieckhefer|first=Robert|title=Is slate making passe?|magazine=Illinois Issues|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=January 1982|accessdate=July 24, 2017|url=http://www.lib.niu.edu/1982/ii820102.html}}</ref> In 1983, rather than run for an eleventh term, Pierce chose to retire. He was succeeded by fellow Democrat and former Lake County Clerk [[Grace Mary Stern]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Glencoe man chosen to challenge Stern|newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|location=[[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]|date=December 12, 1985|accessdate=July 24, 2017|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/daily-herald-suburban-chicago-dec-12-1985-p-5}}{{paywall}}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of Highland Park==\nPierce was elected Mayor of Highland Park in 1987 and reelected in 1991. In 1995, he was defeated for a third term by Trustee Raymond Geraci. He defeated Geraci in the 1999 election and served a final term from 1999 to 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-04-28/news/9504280370_1_highland-park-city-hall-legislature|last=Kuczka|first=Susan|title=Highland Park Has A Friend In Ex-mayor|date=April 28, 1995|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"2003 Resolution\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/fulltext.asp?DocName=&SessionId=3&GA=93&DocTypeId=HR&DocNum=273&GAID=3&LegID=6852&SpecSess=&Session=|title=Full Text of House Resolution 0273 93rd General Assembly|publisher=[[Illinois General Assembly]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=May 9, 2003|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other political activities==\nPierce was later the President of the [[North Shore Water Reclamation District]], a position he served in for over a decade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151230/news/151239937/|author=<!--Daily Herald Report-->|title=Pierce remains leader at North Shore Sanitary District|date=December 30, 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|location=[[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> Pierce was also a member of the Central Committee for the [[Democratic Party of Illinois]] from [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]]. He served on the central committee at various times starting no later than the 1960s, when he was the central committeeman from what was then [[Illinois's 12th congressional district]].<ref name=\"Blue Book 1967-1968\" />\n\n==Death==\nPierce died on February 13, 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Reader comments closed for the holiday weekend|date=February 14, 2020|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|accessdate=February 16, 2020|url=https://capitolfax.com/2020/02/14/reader-comments-closed-for-the-holiday-weekend-56/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Daniel M. Pierce|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 16, 2020|work=Chicago Tribune Media Group Publication|publisher=[[Legacy.com]]|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/chicagotribune/obituary.aspx?n=daniel-m-pierce&pid=195420122}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pierce, Daniel M.}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Highland Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential electors]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lawyer}}\n{{for|the fictional character|Perception (U.S. TV series)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Daniel Pierce\n|image           = \n|alt             = \n|office          = Mayor of [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|term_start      = 1999 \n|term_end        = 2003\n|predecessor     = [[Raymond Geraci]]\n|successor       = [[Michael Belsky]]\n|term_start2     = 1987\n|term_end2       = April 24, 1995\n|predecessor2    = ?\n|successor2      = [[Raymond Geraci]]\n|office3         = Member of the<br>[[Illinois House of Representatives]]<br>from the 58th district<br>{{small|32nd district (1967-1983); At large (1965-1967)}}\n|term_start3     = 1965\n|term_end3       = 1985\n|predecessor3    = ''At large district created''\n|successor3      = [[Grace Mary Stern]]\n<!-- personal -->\n|birth_name      = Daniel Marshall Pierce\n|birth_date      = {{Birth date|1928|3|31}}\n|birth_place     = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|death_date      =  {{Death date and age|2020|2|13|1928|3|31}}\n|death_place     = [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|death_cause     = \n|resting_place   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|citizenship     = \n|nationality     = \n|party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse          = Rhoda\n|children        = \n|residence       = [[Highland Park, Illinois]]\n|alma_mater      = {{nowrap| [[Harvard College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])}}<br>[[Harvard Law School]] {{small|([[Juris doctor|J.D.]])}}}}\n|occupation      = \n|profession      = Attorney\n<!-- militaryservice -->\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Air Force}}\n|serviceyears = \n|rank         = \n|unit         = {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force Judge Advocate General's Corps|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Marshall Pierce''' (March 31, 1928 \u2013 February 13, 2020) was an American lawyer and politician from [[Illinois]]. He served as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]], as Mayor of [[Highland Park, Illinois]], and as a trustee on the North Shore Water Reclamation District.\n\n==Early life==\nPierce was born March 31, 1928 in Chicago. His family moved to the [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] where he graduated from [[New Trier High School]]. He earned degrees from [[Harvard College]] and [[Harvard Law School]]. He served in the [[United States Air Force Judge Advocate General's Corps]] during the [[Korean War]]. While in the Air Force, he attended the [[Air Command and Staff College|United States Air Force Command & Staff School]]. He then took a position with Altheimer, Gray, Naiburg, Strasburger & Lawton where he would remain for the remainder of his legal career.<ref name=\"Blue Book 1967-1968\">{{cite book|author=<!--staff writer-->|title=Illinois Blue Book 1967-1968|page=255|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|url= http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/ref/collection/bb/id/20934|year=1968|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"2003 Resolution\" />\n\n==Illinois House of Representatives==\nIn an unusual election, Pierce ran on a statewide ballot after the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] ordered an at large election for all 177 members of the Illinois House; the result of partisan gridlock preventing the completion of the decennial reapportionment process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1194.html|title=State Politics|last=Devine|first=Michael J.|year=2005|journal=Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 1965 Illinois Supreme Court Case to resolve the redistricting issue, Pierce's [[Highland Park, Illinois|Highland Park]] home was drawn into the 32nd district which consisted of [[Algonquin Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Algonquin]], [[Dorr Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Dorr]],\n[[Grafton Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Grafton]], and [[Nunda Township, McHenry County, Illinois|Nunda]] townships in [[McHenry County, Illinois|McHenry County]] and [[Cuba Township, Lake County, Illinois|Cuba]], [[Deerfield Township, Lake County, Illinois|Deerfield]], [[Ela Township, Lake County, Illinois|Ela]], [[Fremont Township, Lake County, Illinois|Fremont]], [[Libertyville Township, Lake County, Illinois|Libertyville]],\n[[Shields Township, Lake County, Illinois|Shields]], [[Vernon Township, Lake County, Illinois|Vernon]], [[Wauconda Township, Lake County, Illinois|Wauconda]] and [[West Deerfield Township, Lake County, Illinois|West Deerfield]] townships in [[Lake County, Illinois|Lake County]]. He was reelected as one of the district's three representatives.<ref>{{cite book|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Illinois Blue Book 1967-1968|chapter=Representative Reapportionment: Legal Descriptions for Cook County Representative Districts Other Than Cook County|url=http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/ref/collection/bb/id/20934|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|page=255 & 327|date=|isbn=}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure, he was a member of the Democratic Study Group, a caucus of independent, liberal Democrats. His role in this organization earned him a nominal spot on the leadership team of then-Minority Leader [[Clyde L. Choate]].<ref name=JAFFE>{{cite book|last=Barber|first=Charles M.|title=Judge Aaron Jaffe: Reforming Illinois: A Progressive Tackles State Government|publisher=[[AuthorHouse]]|location=[[Bloomington, Indiana]]|date=April 4, 2016|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=150498384X|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref> Pierce served as a delegate for [[Edmund Muskie]] in the [[1972 United States presidential election|1972 Democratic presidential primary]].<ref name=JAFFE /> He was in favor of the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=<!--none-->|title=Downstate candidates for Illinois House|magazine=Illinois Issues|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=October 1978|page=11}}</ref> He  served as Chairman of the House Revenue Committee, the Mental Health Investigating  Committee,  the  Energy  and Environment   Committee,   the   Illinois   Economic   Fiscal Commission,  and  the  Energy  Resources  Commission He served on the House Public Utilities Committee and as House  Minority  Whip  for  two terms.<ref name=\"2003 Resolution\" />\n\nPierce explored running for the Democratic nomination for [[Illinois Attorney General]] in the 1982 primary, but stepped aside after failing to be slated by the Cook County Democratic Party in favor of [[Neil Hartigan]]. Hartigan would go on to beat incumbent [[Tyrone C. Fahner]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kieckhefer|first=Robert|title=Is slate making passe?|magazine=Illinois Issues|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=January 1982|accessdate=July 24, 2017|url=http://www.lib.niu.edu/1982/ii820102.html}}</ref> In 1983, rather than run for an eleventh term, Pierce chose to retire. He was succeeded by fellow Democrat and former Lake County Clerk [[Grace Mary Stern]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Glencoe man chosen to challenge Stern|newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|location=[[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]|date=December 12, 1985|accessdate=July 24, 2017|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/daily-herald-suburban-chicago-dec-12-1985-p-5}}{{paywall}}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of Highland Park==\nPierce was elected Mayor of Highland Park in 1987 and reelected in 1991. In 1995, he was defeated for a third term by Trustee Raymond Geraci. He defeated Geraci in the 1999 election and served a final term from 1999 to 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-04-28/news/9504280370_1_highland-park-city-hall-legislature|last=Kuczka|first=Susan|title=Highland Park Has A Friend In Ex-mayor|date=April 28, 1995|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"2003 Resolution\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/fulltext.asp?DocName=&SessionId=3&GA=93&DocTypeId=HR&DocNum=273&GAID=3&LegID=6852&SpecSess=&Session=|title=Full Text of House Resolution 0273 93rd General Assembly|publisher=[[Illinois General Assembly]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|date=May 9, 2003|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other political activities==\nPierce was later the President of the [[North Shore Water Reclamation District]], a position he served in for over a decade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151230/news/151239937/|author=<!--Daily Herald Report-->|title=Pierce remains leader at North Shore Sanitary District|date=December 30, 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|location=[[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> Pierce was also a member of the Central Committee for the [[Democratic Party of Illinois]] from [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]]. He served on the central committee at various times starting no later than the 1960s, when he was the central committeeman from what was then [[Illinois's 12th congressional district]].<ref name=\"Blue Book 1967-1968\" />\n\n==Death==\nPierce died on February 13, 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Reader comments closed for the holiday weekend|date=February 14, 2020|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|accessdate=February 16, 2020|url=https://capitolfax.com/2020/02/14/reader-comments-closed-for-the-holiday-weekend-56/</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Daniel M. Pierce|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 16, 2020|work=Chicago Tribune Media Group Publication|publisher=[[Legacy.com]]|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/chicagotribune/obituary.aspx?n=daniel-m-pierce&pid=195420122}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pierce, Daniel M.}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Highland Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential electors]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_M._Pierce"}
